{Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'In this game, White has not one but two pawn breaks available to him. We could easily remodel Capablanca's words about the Alexander game to fit the new situation: -- 'From the look of the position it seems that White should prepare the pawn advance e3-e4. If Black is able to defeat this plan, or rather to prevent it, then once White has fixed the black pieces on the kingside he should quickly shift his attack to the queenside, and attack b5 with a2-a4.'' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): 'D38: Queen's Gambit Declined: Ragozin Defence (4 Nf3 Bb4) ''} 1. d4 Nf6 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Opening = D38 - Damengambit-Ragosin Verteid /Queen's Gambit-Ragosin Defence'} 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 $5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!?''} Qc7 {?!} 8. g3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 $5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!?''} 10. Bf4 Nfd7 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'N' 'N'} 11. Bg2 {'with the idea' 0-0, Ne5, f4$36$16} Be6 {?!} (11... Rd8) 12. Nxe5 {'with the idea' Rfe1, e4} Nxe5 $6 {The advance of the a- and b-pawns provokes a minority attack. Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?!' JvR: 'The advance of the a- and b-pawns provokes a minority attack.' Neil McDonald: 'White has completed his development and needs to choose his plan. If he succeeded in advancing e3-e4, blasting open the e-file, he would gain a dangerous initiative, which could easily be converted into a direct assault on the black king: after all, White has a powerful pair of bishops as well as two rooks that could easily be brought into the attack. Alternatively, just dominating the e-file with the rooks after e3-e4 would give White excellent winning chances. --- In order to achieve his aim, White needs to play Rfe1 and Nd2, and then all is ready for e3-e4. The game continued:'' 'with the idea' b5} 13. O-O {''} Qa5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'The only way is by sticking his knight on e4, but unfortunately''} 14. Ne4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'Spielmann, himself a master of attack, is aware that if he does nothing, 15 e4! will give the white pieces an irrepressible energy. Therefore he has to block the advance at all costs.'' ! 'with the idea' f3, e4$36$16} Rd8 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): 'last book move. Black threatens to win material: b5xa4''} 15. Qc2 Be7 $2 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?''} 16. b4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'White terminates the opponent with strong threats'} Bxb4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'Black has successfully accomplished his mission, as the e3-e4 advance is no more. However, in order to carry out his plan, he has been obliged to play 14...b5, which has exposed his queenside pawns to attack. Capablanca exploits this factor straightaway.''} 17. Qb2 $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'A classic example of the conversion of one advantage into another. A grandmaster class player like Spielmann would never have dreamt of playing 14...b5 if it hadn't been an essential component of the plan to stop e3-e4. --- Black now has severe difficulties in defending the b5-pawn, as he has no wish to be left with split pawns on a6 and c4 after 17...bxa4.''} f6 $2 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?' Neil McDonald: 'Nonetheless, it looks as if Spielmann has found the saving move: the white bishop on g5 is attacked and when it retreats 18...Bb7, followed by 19...Bc6 if necessary, will hold together the queenside. But Capablanca has a little surprise in store...' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): '?''} 18. Rfb1 $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'Here we see the conversion of the white bishop into three pawns - one of which will be an unstoppable passed pawn.' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): '+-''} (18. Rab1 Be7 19. Qxb7) 18... O-O 19. Bxe5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'So White conquers the e4 point after all.''} fxe5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): '+-' '+-'} 20. Ng5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'The passed pawn on a6 quickly leads to threats' '+-' !} (20. Qxb4 Rd1+ 21. Bf1 Qxb4) 20... Bc3 (20... Bf7 21. Nxf7 Rxf7) 21. Qc2 (21. Qxb7 Bd5 22. Rb5 cxb5 23. Bxd5+ Kh8 24. Ne6 Rg8 25. Ng5) 21... Bf5 22. Be4 g6 (22... Bxe4 23. Qxe4 g6 24. Qc4+ Rd5 25. Ra2) 23. Qa2+ $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'White has no need to queen the pawn immediately, as if he is patient he can get more than a knight for it.''} Kg7 (23... Kh8 24. Rxb7 Rd7 25. Rab1) 24. Rxb7+ Rd7 25. Rab1 Qa6 26. Qb3 {Capablanca got the first price for the best game. Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: 'Capablanca got the first price for the best game.' Neil McDonald: '. --- A splendid display that won the first brilliancy prize at the New York tournament. --- The moral is: if you believe you have made preparations for a pawn advance (or indeed any other plan) that suits the requirements of the position, and the opponent prevents it, look around to see what other opportunities have arisen for you.''} Rxb7 27. Qxb7+ Qxb7 28. Rxb7+ Kg8 29. Bxc6 $18 Rd8 $4 30. Rxa7 Rd6 31. Be4 Bd7 32. h4 Bd4 33. Ra8+ Kg7 34. e3 Bc3 35. Bf3 1-0


