{Nimzowitsch-Spielmann, Stockholm, 1920.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Be2 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nh6 8. Nc3 Nf5 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Bb4 11. Bc3 Bd7 ({Preferable would have been} 11... Bxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Qb4 (12... Qb6 13. Na4 $1) 13. Bb5 O-O 14. Bxc6 Qxb2 15. Na4 Qb4+ 16. Qd2 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5] White would then have had the point c5, Black a backward pawn plus.}) 12. a3 Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 h5 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qd2 Qd8 {(threatening 16...g5)} 16. h3 Na5 ({In order to meet} 16... g5 {with the riposte} 17. g4 hxg4 18. hxg4 Nh4 19. Nxh4 Rxh4 20. Kg2 {followed by} Z0 21. Rh1 {with an advantage to White.}) 17. Rad1 Qb6 18. Rfe1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] (d4 and to a certain degree e5 are now sytematically overprotected, and this strategy makes it possible later to be automatically master of the situation, whatever complications may arise.)} Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Ne2 Ba4 21. Rc1 {(notice how available an overprotector is for service in all directions.)} Bb3 22. Rxc4 Bxc4 23. Ng3 Ne7 {and White with the better position won on the 61st move.} 24. h4 Ng6 25. Nf1 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Ne7 27. Rc1 O-O 28. b4 Nf5 29. Rc5 Qa6 30. Qc3 Qe2 31. Qc2 Nxd4 32. Qxe2 Nxe2+ 33. Kf1 Nf4 34. Rc7 b5 35. g3 Nd3 36. Ke2 Nb2 37. Rxa7 Rc8 38. Nd4 Rc4 39. Nxb5 d4 40. Rc7 d3+ 41. Ke3 Rg4 42. Rc1 g5 43. Nd6 gxh4 44. gxh4 Rxh4 45. Rb1 Rh3+ 46. Kd2 Na4 47. b5 Nb6 48. Rb4 Rf3 49. Nc4 Nd7 50. b6 Nc5 51. b7 Rxf2+ 52. Ke3 Re2+ 53. Kd4 Nxb7 54. Kxd3 Rg2 55. Rxb7 h4 56. Ne3 Rg5 57. Kd4 h3 58. Rb2 Rh5 59. Rh2 f6 60. Nc4 Kf7 61. a4 Kg6 62. a5 fxe5+ 63. Kc5 Kf5 64. a6 Rh7 65. Kb6 Kg4 66. Ne3+ Kg3 67. Nf1+ 1-0


