{To close the "passed pawn" chapter here is my game against Spielmann from the Stockholm Masters Tournament, 1920. (Results: 1st Bogoljubow 12 1/2; 2nd Nimzowitsch 12; 3rd Olson 8; 4th Spielmann 6 1/2; followed by Wendel, Jacobson, Nyholm, Svanberg). The game represents a difficult positional struggle for minute advantages, and the passed pawn only appears later. However the method of stopping Spielmann's seemingly unstoppable passed pawn makes this game a very instructive example in the spirit of subject.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Be2 cxd4 {If this early liquidation of the White center (the c3-pawn disappearing against the c5-pawn) is the best move, then the Black position must be characterized as weak. However, ...Bd7 is probably playable.} 7. cxd4 Nh6 8. Nc3 Nf5 9. Na4 {Combinational. Bb5 is good enough.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 $1 Qa5 11. Bc3 ({Characteristic of this kind of attack is the fact that even Nc3 would have safeguarded the pawns, e.g.} 11. Nc3 Nfxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. a3 Nxe2 14. axb4 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 ({or} 15. Rxa5 {and a draw is probable through opposite colored Bishops and positing a piece on d4.})) 11... Bd7 ({Or} 11... Bxc3+ $1 12. Nxc3 Qb6 (12... Qb4 $2 13. a3 $1) 13. Bb5 O-O 14. Bxc6 Qxb2 15. Na4 Qb4+ 16. Qd2 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ya4c5] and occupation of c5 (square c5 is worth at least as much as a pawn here).}) 12. a3 Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 h5 14. O-O Rc8 15. Qd2 Qd8 {To follow up with ...g5.} 16. h3 $1 Na5 ({Now} 16... g5 {fails because of} 17. g4 {e.g.} hxg4 18. hxg4 Nh4 19. Nxh4 Rxh4 20. Kg2 {with} Z0 21. Rh1 {and advantage for White.}) 17. Rad1 Qb6 18. Rfe1 {[%csl Yd4,Ye5][%cal Gf3e5,Gf3d4,Gd1d4,Ge1e5] Observe how White systematically overprotects the points d4 and even e5 according to the rule that I formulated: "Important strategic points should be over-protected."} Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 20. Ne2 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ye2g3,Rg3f5] To exchange the strong Knight on f5 through Ng3.} Ba4 21. Rc1 Bb3 22. Rxc4 Bxc4 23. Ng3 Ne7 24. h4 $1 Ng6 25. Nf1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Yf1e3,Re3c4] Now the cavalry will go against the sterile Bishop; Ne3 is intended.} Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Ne7 27. Rc1 O-O {[%csl Yc1,Yc2,Yc3,Yc4,Yc5,Yc6,Yc7,Yc8] Spielmann decides to castle anyway since ...Nf5 will protect everything. In the meantime - as a result of all his maneuvers - White has conquered the c-file.} 28. b4 Nf5 29. Rc5 Qa6 30. Qc3 Qe2 {[%csl Ra2,Rb3] With great skill Spielmann has succeeded in obtaining counter chances through his invasion into the White camp, primarily by taking advantage of the weakness on b2 and later on a3.} 31. Qc2 $3 {After long deliberation White decided on this pawn sacrifice.} Nxd4 32. Qxe2 ({Wrong would be} 32. Nxd4 Qe1+ 33. Kh2 Qxe5+) 32... Nxe2+ 33. Kf1 Nf4 {Black is a passed pawn ahead.} 34. Rc7 b5 ({Perhaps} 34... b6 {was more prudent.}) 35. g3 Nd3 36. Ke2 Nb2 37. Rxa7 {This move required deep foresight. Black gets the c-file, however the White King is so "blockade efficient" that the seemingly strongly supported d-pawn cannot progress very well.} Rc8 38. Nd4 Rc4 39. Nxb5 d4 ({After} 39... Rc2+ 40. Kf1 Nd3 41. f4 {would follow.}) 40. Rc7 d3+ 41. Ke3 ({Not to} 41. Kd2 {because of} Re4) 41... Rg4 42. Rc1 g5 {Spielmann doesn't relax!} 43. Nd6 (43. Rb1 {would not be as good because of} Nc4+ 44. Kxd3 Nxe5+ 45. Ke2 gxh4 46. gxh4 Rxh4) 43... gxh4 44. gxh4 Rxh4 45. Rb1 {[%cal Ya7c7,Yc7c1,Yc1b1] An elegant backward movement of the Rook (a7-c7-c1-b1), especially when you consider the presence of the obligatory drop of poison with the Rook on b1, which entices the pawn to wander.} Rh3+ 46. Kd2 {The White King has taken a curcuitous, even exhausting, route to reach the blockade position.} Na4 47. b5 Nb6 48. Rb4 (48. a4 $2 Nxa4 49. b6 Nxb6 50. Rxb6 Rf3 {etc.}) 48... Rf3 49. Nc4 {Death to the blockader!} Nd7 (49... Nxc4+ 50. Rxc4 Rxf2+ 51. Kxd3 Rf3+ 52. Kc2 Rxa3 {the b-pawn would advance without being stopped, i.e.} 53. Rc8+ Kg7 54. b6 Ra2+ 55. Kc3 Ra3+ 56. Kc4 Ra4+ 57. Kb5 {and wins.}) 50. b6 Nc5 51. b7 Rxf2+ {Note how elegantly Black makes use of his dying Knight right up to its last breath. Now there comes an exciting dance around the d3-pawn.} 52. Ke3 Re2+ 53. Kd4 Nxb7 54. Kxd3 $1 {The point, but the win is still very difficult because the h-pawn suddenly becomes dangerous.} Rg2 55. Rxb7 h4 56. Ne3 Rg5 57. Kd4 h3 58. Rb2 Rh5 59. Rh2 f6 60. Nc4 Kf7 61. a4 {Here the game was adjourned and Spielmann resigned withour resuming play. After} Kg6 62. a5 fxe5+ 63. Kc5 Kf5 64. a6 Rh7 65. Kb6 Kg4 {[%csl Gh2,Rh3][%cal Yc4e3,Ye3f1,Rf1h2] The Knight will arrive just in time by means of Ne3+ and Nf1 to support the blockader on h2 effectively. An extremely valuable game.} 1-0


