1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 c5 3. Bb2 Nc6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Ne5 {(Arriving at the Dutch formation.)} Rc8 ({H. Wolf, Carlsbad, 1923, played here} 10... Nd7 {and there followed} 11. Ndf3 Rc8 12. Qe2 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Be8 14. Qg4 f5 15. Qe2 Bf6 16. c4 Qe7 17. f4 {In the sequel White initiated a strong attack with} Z0 18. h3 Z0 19. Kh2 Z0 20. Rf2 Z0 21. Rg1 Z0 22. g4 {and won.}) 11. f4 Nd7 12. Qg4 Nxe5 ({If} 12... f5 13. Qxg7+ Kxg7 14. Nxc6+ Bf6 15. Nxd8 Bxb2 16. Nxe6+ {and wins.}) 13. Bxe5 ({The alternative} 13. fxe5 {could also be played, e.g.} Bd7 14. Rf3 f5 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Rxf6 Qxf6 18. Rf1 Qe5 19. Qf4 Qxf4 20. exf4 {[%cal Yd2f3,Yf3e5] with a slight superiority in the center (Nf3-e5).}) ({Or} 13. fxe5 Qa5 14. Rf2 {and White has to choose between} Z0 15. e4 ({or the maneuver} 15. Nf1 {followed by} Z0 16. Ng3 {and} Z0 17. Nh5 {Compare to the notes following Black's 11th move in the following move.}) 15... Z0 16. exd5 Bxd5 {(the Black Bishop must now recapture) equalizing the game.}) 13... Bf6 14. Rf3 Bxe5 15. fxe5 Qc7 ({Now} 15... Qa5 {would be useless because of} 16. Rg3 {and} g6 17. Nf3) 16. Qh5 h6 ({The liberating move ...f5 is not yet possible (e.g.} 16... f5 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 19. Qg4+) ({But Black should have prepared for it by} 16... Be8 17. Rh3 h6 18. Nf3 f5 {and White's attack would have been difficult to carry out.}) 17. Raf1 g6 ({A clear superiority in the center could have been attained by White against 17...Be8 (instead of g6) e.g.} 17... Be8 18. Rg3 f5 19. Qxh6 Qxe5 {[%cal Re5g3] (threatening Qxg3)} 20. Qf4 Qf6 21. Nf3) ({Less clear, after} 17... Be8 {would be the sacrificial continuation} 18. Rf6 Qa5 {(always the same sortie by the Queen!)} 19. Rxh6 gxh6 {etc.}) 18. Qxh6 Qxe5 19. Rf6 {[%cal Yg2g4,Yf1f3,Yf3h3]} Qh5 {(White threatened to become unpleasant after g4 and R1f3-h3. The move costs a pawn and Black struggles on for a long time, but without avail.)} 20. Qxh5 gxh5 21. Nf3 Rc7 22. Rh6 f6 23. Nh4 Be8 24. Rfxf6 Rxf6 25. Rxf6 Re7 26. Kf2 {[%csl Re4,Ye5,Yf4,Rf5,Yf6,Yg3,Rg4,Yg5,Rg6,Yh6] (White must maneuver on the dark squares as required by the logic of the game. Because White preferred to win the f-pawn rather than the h-pawn seems to indicate that the first player did not misjudge the situation. A weak move at a later stage, however, unnecessarily prolonged Black's resistance.)} Kg7 27. Rf4 Bd7 28. Ke2 {[%csl Ye5,Yg5] (This is the mistake. He should have played Ke1, when the inherent strength of the dark squares manifests itself most impressively. "Play on the dark squares" would usually incline one to think only of e5 and g5.)} e5 29. Rf5 Re8 30. Rf2 ({The position of the White King now makes} 30. Rxh5 {impossible because of} Bg4+) 30... e4 31. Rf4 {(Slowly but surely he creates again a foundation on dark squares.)} Re5 32. Kd2 b5 33. g3 Bh3 {[%cal Rh4g6,Rh4f5,Rh4f3,Rh4g2,Ge4f3,Gh3f5,Ge5f5,Gg7g6,Gh3g2] (The Knight is now temporarily a prisoner.)} 34. d4 cxd4 35. exd4 Rg5 36. c3 a5 37. Rf2 a4 38. Ke3 a3 39. Rc2 Bf1 40. Rc1 Bd3 41. Ng2 {(The position is reversed. Now the Bishop is the prisoner and the Knight dances around swinging his club.)} Rf5 42. Nf4 Kf7 43. Rd1 {(Now Nxd3 is threatened, which on the last move would have been impossible because of ...Rf3+.)} Ke7 44. Nxd3 exd3 45. b4 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Ye3d2,Yd2c2,Yc2b3] (Free the square b3 for his King. The d-pawn can wait.)} Kd6 46. Kxd3 Rf2 47. Rd2 Rf3+ 48. Kc2 Ke6 49. Re2+ Kd6 50. Kb3 Rd3 51. Re5 h4 52. gxh4 Rh3 53. Rh5 Kc6 54. Rh6+ Kb7 55. h5 {Black resigns.} 1-0


