{[%evp 0,131,26,22,55,56,59,28,23,-35,0,4,14,8,77,-32,-14,-37,-31,-20,-20,-42,13,30,55,-25,-15,-44,33,1,9,37,31,-15,9,4,53,66,87,51,51,2,11,8,8,8,7,28,54,55,51,38,77,59,75,62,63,83,46,-154,111,89,76,-189,-241,-221,-189,-106,-106,-171,0,-86,-37,-273,-212,-246,-246,-246,-246,-246,-219,-260,-175,-175,-170,-174,-171,-170,-151,-373,-80,-55,120,148,122,80,328,223,218,260,276,195,247,265,263,256,311,293,308,266,271,258,302,258,348,285,322,335,426,388,361,370,579,426,565,560,558,593,611,638,721,685,684,684]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 e6 4. Bd3 {It is not a popular line.} ({Another move which is quite rare now is} 4. Be3 {Smyslov has played this move several times.} dxe4 5. Nd2 Nf6 6. fxe4 e5 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Qe2 Nxe5 9. Ngf3 Bg4 10. Qf2 {1/2 (10) Spielmann,R-Tartakower,S Vienna 1913} Nbd7) 4... c5 {which is also a logical move. Surprisingly, it is not so easy.} ({Of course, Black can just take the pawn.} 4... dxe4 {Taking with the bishop is stupid so} 5. fxe4 e5 (5... Qxd4 6. Nf3 Qd8 {is probably the best.} ({If} 6... Qb6 7. Nbd2 {and Nc4 is necessary to consider. I am not sure if immediately because now there is a check on e3.} (7. Qe2 {firstly probably and if some move like} Nd7 {then} 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Be4e5,Bd2c4] with the idea Nc4. It is also possible to push e5 and then prepare Nbd2-c4.})) {Anyway, White has some compensation, for example} 7. e5 {[%cal Bd1e2] then Qe2 and then White has a choice between short and long castle. It is a very complicated position because Black has no real weakness but it is an interesting play.}) 6. dxe5 (6. Nf3 exd4 7. Bc4) 6... Be6) ({Another logical move if Black just wants to avoid any complications is to just play} 4... b6 5. Ne2 Ba6 {then exchange the bishops and try to finish the development. For instance,} 6. Nbc3 Nf6 {[%cal Bf8e7,Be8g8] Black's idea is to provoke e5 Nfd7 and in this French structure, exchanging the bishops is quite a good positional idea for Black. If White doesn't play e5, Black can just play Be7 and 0-0 and at some moment play c5.} 7. e5 Nfd7) 5. c3 {Is strange somehow but it works tactically. Black cannot take on d4 immediately because of Bb5+.} Nc6 6. Ne2 Qb6 7. Bc2 {White just defends the pawn.} Nf6 {Frankly speaking, I don't like this move.} ({In my opinion, much more precise was} 7... Bd7 {And now, for example, after} 8. O-O {some interesting variations can appear, for instance} cxd4 {has the minus that the knight will come to c3 soon. But there is a concrete idea.} 9. cxd4 {[%cal Bb1c3]} Nxd4 {immediately is probably not so good.} ({I can propose another version for Black.} 9... dxe4 10. fxe4 {and only now} Nxd4 (10... e5 {is also possible to consider but White has compensation after} 11. Nbc3 {with the knight coming to d5.}) {If 11.Qxd4 Bc5. If 11.Be3 Nxe2 and Qc7 so} 11. Nxd4 Bc5 12. Be3 e5 {Now Black is preparing to take on d4, so} 13. Ba4 {One of the variations I have considered is} Nf6 14. Bxd7+ Nxd7 15. Qf3 ({Although} 15. Nf5 Bxe3+ 16. Kh1 {is possible to consider but I don't know what it is after} Bd4 {It is a totally messy position. 17.Nxg7+ Kf8 18.Nf5 - so this is possible.}) {Black can just take with the bishop.} 15... Bxd4 16. Qxf7+ Kd8 {[%cal Bh8f8] Probably Black is better because Rf8 is coming. This line is a good illustration of the possibilities but it is very far from forcing.}) 10. Nxd4 {is certainly the best.} (10. Qxd4 {is possible to consider.} Bc5 11. Be3 Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Qc7 {Black has problems with the bishop on c2 hanging. But the idea is some variations can be considered.}) 10... Bc5 11. Be3 e5 {If} 12. Nc3 {it is not finished. It looks bad for Black but, actually, the position is totally unclear after} Nf6 {which is the correct move. For example,} 13. Na4 Bxa4 14. Bxa4+ Kf8 {It is a very sharp game and it is difficult to understand what the evaluation is. Probably, exactly here, White is better after} 15. b4 Bxd4 16. Bxd4 {and then e5 is coming so probably White is better.}) 8. O-O ({White can just play a very good version of the French.} 8. e5 Nd7 9. f4) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 e5 10. Nbc3 exd4 11. Na4 Qc7 12. e5 Nd7 13. Bf4 Nc5 14. e6 Qa5 15. exf7+ Kxf7 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. Kh1 Be6 18. a3 Qb6 19. b4 Be7 20. Qb1 Kg8 21. b5 Na5 22. Be5 Nc4 23. Bxd4 Qc7 24. Bf5 Bf7 25. Qd3 Re8 26. Rfe1 Bf8 27. Nc3 Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1 Nxa3 29. Bxg7 Bxg7 30. Nxd5 Qa5 31. Ne7+ Kf8 32. Rc1 Nc4 33. Nd5 Nd6 34. Nc7 Be5 35. f4 Bc4 36. Qe3 Bf6 37. Ne6+ Kf7 38. Bg4 h5 39. Ng5+ Kg7 40. Bd7 Qd8 41. Ne6+ Bxe6 42. Bxe6 h4 43. Rd1 Qe7 44. Qh3 Rh6 45. f5 Rh5 46. Qg4+ Rg5 47. Qf4 Nf7 48. Rd7 Qxd7 49. Bxd7 Ne5 50. Qe4 Rg4 51. Qxb7 Ra4 52. Kg1 Ra1+ 53. Kf2 Ra2+ 54. Ke3 Kh6 55. Bc6 Kg5 56. Qh7 Ra4 57. h3 Nc4+ 58. Ke2 Kf4 59. Qh6+ Ke5 60. Qc1 Ra2+ 61. Kf3 Ra3+ 62. Kg4 Kd4 63. Kh5 Kc5 64. Qh6 Be7 65. f6 Bd6 66. f7 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0


