{Lasker, Em.: '[Vienna Game]' Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'Lasker, Em.: '[Vienna Game]'''} 1. e4 {Breutigam,Martin Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR JvR: 'Lasker, Em.''} e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 $6 {Breutigam,Martin: 'Wilhelm Steinitz too had often met 3...d5 with 4.d3, and indeed quite successfully. But the fact that this slow move can be nothing special was demonstrated by world champion Emanuel Lasker at the tournament in the international chess congress in St. Petersburg 1909.' Breutigam,Martin: 'Auch Wilhelm Steinitz hatte auf 3...d5 oft mit 4.d3 geantwortet, und zwar mit gutem Erfolg. Dass dieser langsame Zug aber nichts Besonderes sein kann, demonstrierte Weltmeister Emanuel Lasker beim Turnier zum internationalen Schachkongress in St. Petersburg 1909.'} ({Theory is} 4. fxe5 {Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR'} Nxe4 5. Nf3 {(Loewenthal-Staunton, London 1856).}) ({But Auch} 4. Nf3 $6 {Breutigam,Martin also changes nothing. ist indifferent:} exf4 5. exd5 (5. e5 Ne4) 5... Nxd5 {; It will not be easy for White to recover the pawn he has sacrificed, e.g.. ; Weiß wird es nicht leicht fallen, den geopferten Bauern zurückzugewinnen, z.B.} 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. d4 Be7 8. Be2 (8. Bxf4 $4 Qe4+) 8... g5 $15) 4... exf4 $1 {Lasker, Em.: '[The simplest.]' Breutigam,Martin: 'Lasker, after the tournament which he won together with Akiba Rubinstein,wrote a book about it. In his annotations to this game Lasker wrote after 4...exf4: "The simplest. 5.e4-e5 can now be met with d5-d4." JvR: 'Lasker, Em.: '[The simplest.]''' Breutigam,Martin: 'Lasker selbst verfasste nach dem Meisterturnier, das er gemeinsam mit Akiba Rubinstein gewonnen hatte, ein Buch darüber. In seinen Kommentaren zu dieser Partie schrieb Lasker nach 4...exf4: "Am einfachsten. Auf 5.e4-e5 kann nun d5-d4 kommen."'} ({The alternatives are less clear, e.g. Weniger deutlich sind die Alternativen, z.B.} 4... dxe4 {Breutigam,Martin} 5. fxe5 Ng4 6. Nxe4 Nxe5 7. d4 Ng6 8. Nf3 Qe7 9. Bd3 f5 10. Bg5 Qe6 11. O-O fxe4 12. Bxe4 Bd6 13. Ne5 Bxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Qh5 Ndf8 16. Rad1 Bd7 17. h3 Rg8 18. Kh1 Qb6 19. e6 Bxe6 20. Rd2 a5 21. b3 a4 22. Rfd1 Bd7 23. Rxd7 {1-0 (23) Steinitz,W-Neumann,G Baden-Baden 1870}) (4... d4 {Breutigam,Martin} 5. Nce2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6 7. c3 {1-0 (18) Steinitz,W-Papot,A Haarlem 1896}) ({And Und} 4... Bb4 {Breutigam,Martin} 5. fxe5 Nxe4 $5 {would lead to the same drawn position as after the variation with 4.fxe5 xe4 5.d3 b4 (5...d4! is more ambitious): würde zur gleichen Remis-Stellung führen wie die Variante 4.fxe5 xe4 5.d3 b4 (ambitionierter ist 5...d4!):} 6. dxe4 Qh4+ 7. Ke2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 Qg4+ {The simplest way to draw. Der einfachste Remisweg.} ({another known one is bekannt ist auch} 8... Bg4+ 9. Nf3 dxe4 10. Qd4 Bh5 $1 11. Ke3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Qe1+ 13. Kf4 Qh4+ 14. Ke3 Qe1+ {½-½ (14) Nunn,J (2590)-Short,N (2615) Krefeld 1986}) 9. Ke1 Qh4+ 10. Ke2 {½-½, Borg, G (2385)-Zysk,R (2390), Munich 1986}) 5. Bxf4 ({Breutigam,Martin: 'As Lasker pointed out ' Breutigam,Martin: 'Wie Lasker bemerkte, würde '} 5. e5 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '?' Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'Lasker, Em.'' can be met by Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'can be met by''} d4 {Breutigam,Martin: '!' Breutigam,Martin: 'would actually lead to an advantage for Black,e.g.' Breutigam,Martin: 'tatsächlich zu schwarzem Vorteil führen, z.B.'} 6. exf6 {Breutigam,Martin} dxc3 7. Qe2+ Be6 8. bxc3 Qxf6 $17) 5... Bb4 {Breutigam,Martin: '!'} 6. exd5 (6. e5 $2 {Breutigam,Martin} d4 $1 $17) 6... Nxd5 7. Bd2 Bxc3 {!} (7... O-O 8. Nxd5 Re8+ 9. Be2 Qxd5 10. Nf3 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Nc6 12. c3 {(Lombardy - Garcia P., Lone Pine, 1977)} Bf5 $13) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Nf3 Re8+ 10. Be2 {Breutigam,Martin: '?!'} (10. Kf2 {Breutigam,Martin}) 10... Qe7 {Breutigam,Martin: '' ''} 11. c4 $1 {Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: '!''} Nf6 12. Bg5 Nc6 {Breutigam,Martin: '?!'} ({More pressure keeps Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'More pressure keeps''} 12... Nbd7 $1 {!?} 13. Qd2 {Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR'} (13. Rb1 b6 14. d4 Bb7 $15) 13... b6) 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. O-O Bg4 ({Here Breutigam,Martin: 'Lasker afterwards preferred JvR: 'Here'' Breutigam,Martin: 'Hinterher gefiel Lasker'} 14... Qh6 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'Lasker, Em.'' %03'better is' would have been much stronger. Breutigam,Martin: ': "If then JvR: 'would have been much stronger.'' Breutigam,Martin: 'besser: "Wenn dann'} {If Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'If''} 15. Rf2 {Breutigam,Martin: ',' Breutigam,Martin: ','} Bg4 16. Bf1 {Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR'} (16. Qc1 {Breutigam,Martin} Re3 {! White cannot free himself from the pressure." Weiß kann sich von dem Drucke nicht befreien."}) 16... Re3 {and White cannot free himself from the pressure.}) 15. Qd2 (15. Kh1 Qe6 $15) 15... Nd4 16. Rae1 Bxf3 {Breutigam,Martin: '?!' Breutigam,Martin: 'Black's advantage is disappears noticeably.' Breutigam,Martin: 'Der schwarze Vorteil verschwindet zusehends.'} ({If} 16... Rxe2 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '(JvR) Lasker, Em.' ?} 17. Rxe2 Bxf3 ({if} 17... Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Bxf3 {then} 19. Rg2 Qb6+ 20. c5 Qxc5+ 21. d4 {or 21.f2 and White has the Exchange for two pawns.} (21. Qf2 {Lasker})) 18. Ref2 Qb6 19. c3 Ne2+ 20. Kh1 {and Black is in difficulties.}) ({A stronger move was Stärker war} 16... Nxe2+ {Breutigam,Martin !?} 17. Rxe2 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 (19. Rxf3 $4 Qb1+) 19... Qb2 $15 {[%csl Ra2]} (19... Qc6 $15)) 17. Bxf3 Rxe1 18. Qxe1 ({Not Nicht} 18. Rxe1 $4 {Breutigam,Martin} Qxf3 $1 $19) 18... Nxc2 (18... Qb6 {!?}) 19. Qf2 Nd4 ({Useless would be} 19... Nb4 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '(JvR) Lasker, Em.' ?!} 20. Bxb7 Qxf2+ 21. Rxf2 Rd8 (21... Re8 22. Be4 {Lasker}) 22. Be4) 20. Bxb7 Qxf2+ 21. Kxf2 ({Far better than} 21. Rxf2 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '(JvR) Lasker, Em.' ?!} Rb8 22. Bd5 $2 {?} Rb1+ 23. Rf1 Ne2+ 24. Kf2 Rxf1+ 25. Kxf1 Nc3 {Lasker and wins the a-pawn as White cannot afford to let the Bishop be taken.}) 21... Rb8 ({Better} 21... Re8 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '(JvR) Lasker, Em.' ! at once.} 22. Bd5 $13) 22. Bd5 Re8 (22... Nf5 23. c5 Rb5 24. Re1 Kf8 25. Re5 Nh6 26. Re8+ Kxe8 27. Bc6+ Ke7 28. Bxb5 Nf5 29. Bc6 $14) 23. Bf3 ({White should take possession of the b-file with the Rook by} 23. Rb1 {Lasker, Em. Breutigam,Martin: '(JvR) Lasker, Em.' !? for then Black would achieve nothing by} Re2+ {?} ({but would have to be satisfied with a draw with} 23... c6 24. Bf3 Kf8 25. Rb7 Re7 26. Rb8+ {= etc.}) 24. Kf1 {'with the idea' Rb7 'with the idea' Rb8 as both 25.b7 and 25.b8+ would be threatened.}) (23. Kg3 {!?} Rf8 24. c5 c6 25. Bc4 h6 26. Rf4 $14) 23... Re6 24. Rb1 Rb6 25. Rxb6 axb6 26. c5 $1 {Spielmann solves his difficulties elegantly. Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: '!' JvR: 'Spielmann solves his difficulties elegantly.'' !? Lasker, Em.: '[An ingenious idea, which secure the draw.]' Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'Lasker, Em.: '[An ingenious idea, which secure the draw.]'''} Kf8 ({Lasker, Em.: 'If Black takes'} 26... bxc5 $2 {Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR' Lasker, Em.: 'White plays'} 27. a4 Nb3 28. Bd5 Na5 29. Ke3 {endangers Black.}) (26... b5 {!?} 27. Be4 $13) 27. cxb6 {''} cxb6 28. Bd5 Ke7 29. Ke3 Ne6 30. d4 f5 31. h4 (31. Kd3 Nf4+ 32. Kc4 Kd6 33. Bf3 Ne6 34. a4 g5 35. Bd5 Nf4 $13) 31... g6 {''} (31... Kd6 32. Bf3 b5 {?!} 33. d5 Nf8 34. Kd4 Ng6 35. h5 Nh4 36. Be2 f4 37. Ke4 Nxg2 38. Bxb5 $16) 32. Bf3 h6 33. Bd5 (33. d5 Nc5 34. Kd4 Kd6 35. Bd1 Ne4 36. Be2 g5 37. hxg5 hxg5 38. Bd3 Nf6) 33... g5 34. hxg5 hxg5 35. Bc4 Kf6 (35... Kd6 36. Bd3 Nf4 37. Bxf5 Nxg2+ 38. Ke4 Nf4 39. a4 Ne2 40. Kd3 Nf4+ 41. Kc4 Nd5 {=}) 36. Bb3 Nf4 37. Kf3 (37. g3 {!?} Nh5 38. Kf2 Ke7 39. Bc4 Kd6 40. Kf3 Ng7 41. a4 Ne6 {=}) 37... Ng6 (37... Ne6) 38. g3 {Lasker, Em.: '[Adjourned.]' Breutigam,Martin: 'JvR: 'Lasker, Em.: '[Adjourned.]'''} Ne7 (38... Ke7 39. Bc2 Ke6 40. Bd3 Ne7 41. Bc4+ Kd6 42. Bd3 Ke6 {=}) 39. Bc4 (39. Ke3 {!?} Nc6 40. a3 Ke7 41. d5 Ne5 42. Bc2 Nc4+ 43. Kd4 Nd6 44. Bd3 Kf6 {=}) 39... Nc6 40. Ke3 Nb4 41. Bb3 (41. Kd2 Nc6 42. Kc3 f4 43. gxf4 gxf4 {=}) 41... Ke7 42. Kf3 Nc6 43. Ke3 Kd6 44. Bc2 Ne7 45. Bb3 Nd5+ 46. Kf3 Nc3 47. Ke3 (47. Bc2 {!?} Ke6 48. Bd3 Kd5 49. Bxf5 Kxd4