{This was the first game in which the thesis of the relative harmlessness of the pawn roller was stated. Tartakower,SG: '500 Master Games of Chess by S. Tartakower and J. Du Mont BOOK 2: SEMI-OPEN GAMES 18. The Sicilian Defence # 309   '} 1. e4 {Tartakower,SG} c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 $5 {Spielmann looks with mistrust at the naughty black knight. Finally he decides against a knight hunt and makes a prudent move. This set Spielmann thinking. After some minutes Nimzo raised his eyes from the board and saw that his opponent was quite disconcerted. He looked at the Knight now confidently, now suspiciously, and after much hesitation gave up the possible chase started by 3.e5 and played the much more circumspect 3.Nc3. The next year Nimzo tried 2... Nf6 on Schlechter, and in the book of the Congress we find the following note to this move by Tarrasch; "Not good, since the Knight is at once driven away, but Herr Nimzowitsch goes his own road in the openings, one, however, which cannot be recommended to the public." Ridicule can do much, for instance embitter the existence of young talents, but one thing is not given to it, to put a stop permanently to the incursion of new and powerful ideas. The old dogmas, such as the ossified teaching of the center, the worship of the open game, and in general the whole formalistic conception of the game, who bothers himself today about these? (Nimzo sounds torqued!) The new ideas, however, those supposed to be by-ways, not to be recommended to the public, these are becoming today (1925) highways, on which great and small move freely in the consciousness of absolute security. Tartakower,SG: 'Christoph Scheerer: 'It is interesting to quote Nimzowitsch's own observation of this game in order to get a better feeling about the impact his idea must have made: 'This set Spielmann thinking. After some minutes I raised my eyes from the board and saw that my dear old companion in arms was quite disconcerted. He looked at the knight, now confidently, now suspiciously, and after much hesitation gave up the possible chase started by 3 e5 and played the more circumspect 3 Nc3.'''} 3. Nc3 ({As noted above,} 3. e5 {(Tartakower,SG) is the critical try and will be examined more closely below.}) 3... d5 $5 4. exd5 (4. e5 {Tartakower,SG} Ne4 (4... Nfd7 5. Nxd5 Nxe5 6. Ne3 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nc6) 5. Ne2 {Christoph Scheerer: 'is an idea that can also be found in Alekhine's Defence; White wants to exploit the rather exposed position of the black knight, but after'} (5. Bb5+) 5... c4 {Christoph Scheerer: '!'} 6. d3 cxd3 7. cxd3 Qa5+ 8. Nd2 Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Qb6 10. Bc3 Nc6 11. d4 Bg4 12. f3 Bf5 {Black was already better in E.Sergeant-S.Tartakower, Hastings 1927}) ({Besides the text move there are two alternatives worth mentioning:} 4. Bb5+ {(Tartakower,SG) is a move without any ambition. After} Bd7 5. Bxd7+ ({alternatively,} 5. exd5 Bxb5 6. Nxb5 Nxd5 {is very equal,}) ({while} 5. e5 Ne4 {transposes to variation 'b' below} 6. Bxd7+ (6. e6 fxe6 7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ng5 Nf6 10. Nxe6 Qd6 11. Nxf8 Rxf8 12. O-O O-O-O {led to a very messy position in V.Goldberg-C.Wichmann, German League 2000; Black's pawn structure is badly compromised, but on the other hand his pieces are very active and, indeed, I would prefer Black here}) 6... Qxd7 7. Ne2 c4 8. d3 cxd3 9. cxd3 Nc5 10. Be3 Ne6 11. O-O Nc6 {and the game is equal according to Khalifman.}) 5... Qxd7 6. exd5) 4... Nxd5 5. Bc4 ({'Theory' will become} 5. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 {(Tartakower,SG) there is a further branch:} 6. Z0 (6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {transposes to note 'a' to White's 4th move.} 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. d4 {(White has to play this move before Black can prevent it with 8...Nc6)} e6 9. Be3 c4 (9... cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 a6) 10. c3 Nc6 11. O-O Bd6 {Black had a good position with a well-centralized queen in B.Bednay-E.Kahn, Budapest 2007.}) ({. Against} 6. Qe2 {Joszef Horvath recommends the as yet untested} Bxb5 $5 7. Qxb5+ Nc6 8. Qxb7 Ndb4 9. Qb5 Rb8 10. Qa4 Rb6 11. O-O Ra6 12. Qb5 ({or} 12. Qb3 Na5 13. Qa4+ Nac6) 12... Ra5 13. Qc4 Nxc2 14. Rb1 N2d4 15. Nxd4 Qxd4 16. d3 Qxc4 17. dxc4 g6 {with equality.}) (6. Ne5 Bxb5 $1 7. Qf3 f6 {leads to sharp play involving an exchange sacrifice by Black. After} 8. Nxb5 Na6 ({obviously bad is} 8... fxe5 $2 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nc7+ Kd7 11. Nxd5 {when Black has no compensation for his demolished structure}) 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qxh8 Qd7 {we have reached a position in which a complicated struggle lies ahead. One example of how play could evolve was} 12. Nc3 (12. Qg8 O-O-O 13. Nc3 Nf4 {gave Black serious counterplay in V.Talla-J.Hudecek, Czech League 2007}) 12... Qe6+ 13. Kf1 Nab4 14. Qh3 ({or} 14. Qh4 Qa6+ 15. Kg1 Nxc2 {with good chances for Black in K.Spraggett-J.De La Villa Garcia, Dos Hermanas 2006}) 14... Qxh3 15. gxh3 Nc7 {with good compensation for Black as the white c-pawn is about to fall.})) (5. Nxd5 {Tartakower,SG} Qxd5 6. d4 e6 (6... Bg4 7. Be2 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Bxe2 10. Kxe2 a6 {led to quick equality in F.Bindrich-A.Anastasian, Dresden 2007.})) ({Christoph Scheerer: 'Again White has a large number of alternatives:'} 5. d4 {Tartakower,SG} Nxc3 6. bxc3 e6 (6... g6 {leads to a favourable Grünfeld-like structure due to White's rather inflexible pawn centre.}) 7. Bd3 Be7) (5. Ne5 {(Tartakower,SG) Christoph Scheerer: '!?' Christoph Scheerer: 'forces Black to be a bit careful, but after'} Nxc3 6. bxc3 ({Christoph Scheerer: 'or'} 6. Qf3 Qd5 7. Qxc3 Nd7 8. Bb5 a6 {Christoph Scheerer: 'and Black has freed his game as analysed by Tartakower'}) 6... Qd5 (6... Qc7 7. Bb5+ Nd7 8. Qe2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 O-O 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bb4 14. Bd2 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Rd8 16. Bd3 b6 17. Qf4 Bb7 18. Qh4 g6 {Black had equalized in S.Tarrasch-S.Tartakower, Berlin 1928.}) 7. Bb5+ Nd7 (7... Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Be2 Qxg2 10. Bf3 Qg6) 8. Qe2 a6 (8... Qxg2 9. Qd3 Qxh1+ 10. Ke2 e6 11. Bxd7+) 9. Bxd7+ Bxd7 10. O-O) 5... e6 (5... Nxc3 {Tartakower,SG} 6. bxc3 e6) (5... Nb6 {Tartakower,SG} 6. Bxf7+) 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Ne5 $5 Qc7 {What now follows is play against the hanging pawns, which will soon come into existence. Tartakower,SG: 'Christoph Scheerer: 'Black can develop smoothly while White has to take care of his weakened structure.''} (9... Nd7 {Tartakower,SG} 10. f4 Nb6 (10... Nf6 11. Bb2) 11. Be2) 10. Bd3 ({Christoph Scheerer: 'Trying to support the knight with'} 10. f4 {(Tartakower,SG) Christoph Scheerer: '?' Christoph Scheerer: 'does not work after'} cxd4 {Christoph Scheerer: 'when both'} 11. Qe2 ({Christoph Scheerer: 'and'} 11. cxd4 f6 {Christoph Scheerer: 'lose material'}) (11. Qxd4 Bc5 {Christoph Scheerer: 'lose material.'}) 11... dxc3) 10... Nc6 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Re1 (12. Nxc6 {Tartakower,SG} Bxf4) 12... cxd4 {'!' This exchange in conjunction with ...Nb4 is the point of the proceedings started by 9...Qc7.} 13. cxd4 $1 Nb4 {Tartakower,SG: 'Christoph Scheerer: '!''} ({Christoph Scheerer: 'Less accurate would be'} 13... Nxd4 {Tartakower,SG} 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qxd4 {Christoph Scheerer: '.'}) 14. Bg3 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 b6 16. c4 $6 {White's hanging pawns become a target.} ({The exchange} 16. Nf3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 {keeps the equality.}) 16... Ba6 {'=' The hanging pawns, which come under heavy fire, prove in the end to have much vigor. The game is about equal. Tartakower,SG: 'Christoph Scheerer: '. Black can be very satisfied with the outcome of the opening phase: his pawn structure is superior to White's and his two bishops have plenty of scope in this open position. Nimzowitsch eventually converted his advantage in the endgame. --- A successful debut for the Nimzowitsch Sicilian! And it even got better: later that year Nimzowitsch managed to defeat Julius Perlis at Carlsbad, and in the following year (again in San Sebastian) he reached a clearly better endgame against Carl Schlechter. Despite this successful employment, Nimzowitsch's rather eccentric variation was not widely accepted. Tarrasch, for instance, remarked that 2...Nf6 is 'not good, since the knight is at once driven away, but Herr Nimzowitsch goes his own way in the openings; one, however, which cannot be recommended to the public.' To which Nimzowitsch simply answered: 'Ridicule can do much, for instance embitter the existence of young talents; but one thing is not given to it, to put a stop permanently to the incursion of new and powerful ideas.' I can't help it, but I'm with Nimzowitsch on this one; even more so as his overall score with his variation was exceptionally good.''} 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. Qb3 {'!'} f6 $6 19. Qa4 $6 {Black keeps the initiative. '?'} ({Better is} 19. c5 $1 {(Mieses) This would, according to Nimzo, have led to a draw.} fxe5 $1 (19... Bxe5 20. dxe5) 20. Qxe6+ Rf7 $1 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. cxd6 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 exd4) (19. Nf3 {Tartakower,SG} Bxg3 20. hxg3 Bxc4) 19... fxe5 20. dxe5 (20. Qxa6 {Tartakower,SG} exd4 21. Rxe6 Bxg3 22. hxg3 Rxf2 23. Kxf2 Qf7+ 24. Kg1 Qxe6) 20... Ba3 $1 (20... Bxe5 {Tartakower,SG} 21. Rxe5) 21. Qxa3 Bxc4 22. Re4 Qd7 (22... b5 {Tartakower,SG}) 23. h3 (23. Rexc4 {Tartakower,SG} Rxc4 24. Rxc4 Qd1#) (23. Qd6 {Tartakower,SG} Qxd6 (23... Qa4 24. Rexc4 Rxc4 25. Qxe6+) 24. exd6 Bxa2 25. Rxc8 Rxc8 26. Re1 Kf7 (26... Bd5 27. Bh4) (26... Rd8 27. Ra1) 27. Ra1 (27. Bh4 Ke8) (27. Rd1 Bd5) 27... Rc2) 23... Bd5 {With his Bishop posted here, Black's advantage is clear.} 24. Re2 Qb7 25. f4 Qf7 26. Rec2 Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Qg6 28. Qc3 $2 {White cannot give up on the c-file.} (28. Rc3 {White does not fair well in this line...} h5 29. h4 Rxf4 {White's hurtin'.}) 28... Bxa2 $1 {A trick gains a pawn.} 29. Bh4 (29. Rxa2 $2 {Opps! This loses straightaway.} Qb1+) 29... Bd5 30. Be7 Re8 31. Bd6 Qe4 32. Qc7 h6 33. Rf2 Qe1+ 34. Rf1 Qe3+ 35. Rf2 a5 36. Be7 Qe1+ 37. Rf1 Qe3+ 38. Rf2 Kh8 {Directed against the possibility of Bf6.} 39. Bd8 Qe1+ 40. Rf1 Qe3+ 41. Rf2 Qe1+ 42. Rf1 Qg3 43. Rf2 Rf8 44. Qxb6 Rxf4 45. Be7 a4 {A passed pawn and a mating attack - these make a wicked affair.} 46. Kf1 $2 {White was lost in any case.} Qxg2+ {The introduction of an important new variation was successful. Black wins.} 0-1


