{Craig Pritchett: 'According to Jan Pinski, in his 2003 work, The Four Knights, this move "is considered the main move after 4 Bb5 and clearly ... the most dynamic route to equality." Rubinstein was already attracted to this line and played it successfully in the pre-war years, but he refined and developed many of the line's main ideas in the 1920s. In 1925, he played one of his most famous games in this line, against Rudolf Spielmann.'} 1. e4 {1)Kagans Neueste Schachnachrichten 1925. S.316. [Spielmann] 2)Kmoch: Rubinstein gewinnt! S.103} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 {Craig Pritchett: 'Writing about this move in Masters of The Chessboard, Réti makes the point that while the "Spanish Four Knights" (or Four Knights) is less direct than the Spanish Opening (3 Bb5), it is not without guile. Its main aim is to develop pieces early, prior to taking up the battle for control of Black's central strong point e5 in the early middlegame (usually by playing for d4 or f4). --- Hence, Réti writes, "for this reason, the correct reply by Black ...does not lie in mere defence. Rather Black will do best to utilise White's slow and not especially logical play to seize the initiative."'} Nd4 {Craig Pritchett: 'Réti noted that Black's knight on d4 "takes advantage of the fact that ... White is no longer able to move c3 and [that White's] bishop now stands on b5 without any purpose." Black's bold strike in the centre is, however, an extremely demanding as well as a purely logical move. Black must be prepared to continue in tactical style and unafraid to gambit.'} 5. Nxe5 {Craig Pritchett: 'This capture can lead to quite complicated outcomes, but the critical lines are nowadays considered to be 5 Ba4 and 5 Bc4,'} ({whereas other moves are less convincing: After} 5. Ba4 Z0 (5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 O-O 7. Z0 (7. Nd3 $1 Bb6 8. e5 Ne8 9. Nd5 d6 10. Ne3 {, we reach a position that remains subject to major theoretical debate. White has an extra pawn and a healthy pawn structure but tangled minor pieces. Black has a time advantage and can hope to put pressure on White's game, while he struggles to unravel his tangled pieces and complete his queenside development.} (10. Z0)) ({. Instead after the less energetic} 7. d3 $6 {, Black developed an early initiative in one of the first games played in this line, S.Tarrasch-A.Rubinstein, San Sebastian 1912, which continued} d5 8. Bg5 c6 9. Qd2 Re8 10. f4 b5 11. Bb3 h6 12. Bh4 Nxe4 $1 13. Bxd8 Nxd2 14. Kxd2 Rxd8 15. Ne2 Nxe2 16. Kxe2 Re8 17. Kf1 $5 Bb7 18. c3 f6 19. Ng4 h5 20. Nf2 Be3 21. Bd1 h4 22. g3 a5 23. Bf3 b4 24. Kg2 bxc3 25. bxc3 Ba6 26. c4 Rad8 {, and Black went on to win impressively in a famous endgame.})) ({. Earlier} 5... Nxf3+ {is also possible, though far less exciting}) ({, while} 5... c6 6. Nxe5 d6 7. Nf3 Bg4 {, and if} 8. d3 d5 {, is a sharper alternative more in the spirit of the opening.})) ({Matters are also unclear after} 5. Bc4 Z0 (5... Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Z0 (7. Nd3 d5 8. Nxd5 ({the game A.Nimzowitsch-A.Alekhine, St Petersburg 1914, also went well for Black after} 8. Bxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxe4+ 10. Ne3 Bd6 11. O-O Be6 12. Ne1 O-O-O {, and Black went on to win this too}) 8... Qxe4+ 9. Ne3 Bd6 {. The manic attacking game, Z.Belsitzman-A.Rubinstein, Warsaw 1917, continued} 10. O-O $6 (10. f3 Qh4+ 11. Nf2 {improves according to Keitlinghaus}) 10... b5 $1 11. Bb3 Bb7 12. Ne1 Qh4 13. g3 Qh3 14. c3 h5 $1 15. cxd4 h4 16. Qe2 Qxh2+ $1 {0-1.}) ({. White didn't get far either in R.Spielmann-A.Rubinstein, San Sebastian 1912, after} 7. Nf3 $5 d5 8. Z0 (8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nf3 Nxe4 10. O-O O-O 11. d4 cxd3 12. cxd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bg4 14. d4 Bd6 15. Qd3 Rae8 {, and Black went on to outplay his opponent.}) ({Fuzzier perhaps here is} 8. Bxd5 {after which O.Bernstein-A.Rubinstein, Vilnius 1912, continued} Bg4 9. d3 c6 10. Bb3 Nd7 11. Bg5 Qd6 12. Nb1 Qg6 13. Be3 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qg2 15. Kd2 Nxf3+ 16. Kc1 Rd8 17. h3 Bxe3+ 18. fxe3 Nde5 19. Qf1 Qg5 20. Qe2 Nd4 21. Qd2 Ndf3 22. Qe2 Nd4 {, with an eventual draw.}))) ({. As against 5 Ba4, Black can also meet 5 Bc4 with the sharp} 5... c6 {, and if} 6. Nxe5 d5 7. exd5 Bd6) ({, or the less ambitious but solid} 5... Nxf3+ 6. Qxf3 d6 {, and if} 7. d3 Be7 8. O-O O-O {.})) ({Black has nothing to fear after} 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. e5 dxc3 7. exf6 Qxf6 8. dxc3 Be7 ({or} 8... Bc5 9. O-O O-O) 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 c6 11. Bd3 d5 {, A.Brinckmann-A.Rubinstein, Budapest 1929.}) ({Likewise, Black is pretty comfortable after} 5. O-O Nxb5 6. Nxb5 c6 7. Nc3 d6 {, and if} 8. d4 Qc7 9. h3 Be7 10. Be3 O-O {.}) 5... Qe7 6. f4 {Craig Pritchett: '!?' Craig Pritchett: 'Bogoljubow prepared this sharp move for his match against Rubinstein, in Stockholm and Gothenburg 1920. Rubinstein won the match 6½-5½, but wobbled with his favourite anti-Four Knights variation. One of the dangers for White and Black in this line is the scope for deep and sharp opening preparation. Get caught out and you may easily lose against better homework. Five years on, Rubinstein had an improvement in mind on his 10th move.'} ({Modern theory assesses the quieter alternative} 6. Nf3 Nxb5 7. Nxb5 Qxe4+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Kxe2 Nd5 10. Re1 {as roughly equal, after} f6 ({and possibly also} 10... a6 {.})) 6... Nxb5 7. Nxb5 d6 8. Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 {Craig Pritchett: '!?' Craig Pritchett: 'This was the point of Bogoljubow's play in 1920.'} ({Retaining queens, White takes his king on a risky journey, aiming to get his rook to the e-file quickly. Instead Black's bishop-pair may even give Black an edge after the insipid} 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Kd8 {.}) 9... Ng4+ {Craig Pritchett: 'Black continues down the critical path and White also takes up the challenge with his reply.'} 10. Kg3 ({Craig Pritchett: 'Black should be fine after'} 10. Kg1 Kd8 {, as in K.Opocensky-A.Rubinstein, Merano 1924, which continued} ({or possibly} 10... Qc6) 11. h3 Nf6 12. d4 h5 13. Ng5 Qe8 14. Nc3 Bf5 15. Kh2 Ng4+ 16. hxg4 hxg4+ 17. Kg3 Rxh1 18. Qxh1 f6 {, with a double-edged game.}) 10... Qg6 $1 {Craig Pritchett: 'This move, generally attributed to analysis by Richard Teichmann,'} ({improves on} 10... Kd8 $6 11. h3 Nh6 12. d4 Be7 13. Re1 Qg6+ 14. Kh2 Re8 15. c4 {, which allowed White to secure his king and achieve a comfortable spatial advantage in E.Bogoljubow-A.Rubinstein, 3rd matchgame 1920.}) 11. Qe2+ {Craig Pritchett: '!?' Craig Pritchett: 'White forces Black's king to forego its right to castle, but the move also allows Black to cover his c-pawn and secure his kingside development.'} ({Craig Pritchett: 'Much later analysis by Paul Keres, quoted by Pinski, indicates that Black also survives after the complicated alternative' Spielmann: An dieser Stelle wurde schon manches zur Ehrenrettung für Weiß versucht. So} 11. Nh4 {Craig Pritchett: '!?'} Qh5 {Craig Pritchett: '. Keres' beautiful main line then continues'} 12. Nxc7+ {Craig Pritchett: '?!'} (12. Z0) ({. Here Black also stands well after} 12. h3 Qxb5 13. hxg4 g5) ({, or} 12. f5 g5 13. Qxg4 gxh4+ 14. Kf3 Qxg4+ 15. Kxg4 Rg8+ 16. Kf3 Kd8 {.}) 12... Kd8 {Craig Pritchett: '. If instead' Nach} 13. Nxa8 {Craig Pritchett: '?!' Craig Pritchett: ', Keres gives'} ({Eine Zeit lang glaubte man, die Opferspielweise von Schwarz mit dem Zwischenzug} 13. h3 {widerlegt zu haben,} {bis man das Damenopfer} Nf6 14. Nxa8 (14. Qxh5 Nxh5+ 15. Kf2 Kxc7 {würde eine Figur kosten}) 14... Qxh4+ {Craig Pritchett: '!!'} 15. Kxh4 Ne4 $19 {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'and Black catches White's king in a remarkable mating net. White must give up his queen to avoid mate, but Black retains a clear advantage after' mit analytisch einwandfreiem Gewinn für Schwarz entdeckte.} 16. Qh5 Be7+ 17. Qg5 Bxg5+ 18. fxg5 h6 19. g6 fxg6 20. Rf1 g5+ 21. Kh5 Ng3+ 22. Kg6 Nxf1) (13. Z0) 13... g5 {Craig Pritchett: '!' würde der schwarze Angriff allzu heftig werden.} 14. fxg5 ({or} 14. Nf3 gxf4+ 15. Kxf4 d5) 14... Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qg7 {with a winning attack.}) 11... Kd8 12. Re1 ({The earlier R.Spielmann-H.Weenink, Scheveningen 1923, had gone} 12. h3 Nf6+ ({but Black should play} 12... Ne3+ $1 13. Kh2 Nxc2 14. Rb1 c6 $1 {and if} 15. Nc3 Be7 {, with advantage to Black - Pinski}) 13. Kh2 Ne4 14. Qe1 Bd7 15. Nbd4 f5 16. d3 Nf6 17. Qa5 {, and White was better.}) ({Instead} 12. Nh4 $2 {now fails to} Qxc2 {.}) 12... Bd7 13. Nbd4 {Craig Pritchett: 'White has to gambit his c-pawn.'} ({If} 13. c3 $2 Ne3+ 14. Kf2 Nc2 {, and wins with a trivial knight fork.}) 13... Ne3+ {Craig Pritchett: 'Black can only use his discovered check to win White's c-pawn and should do this at once.'} 14. Kf2 ({Not} 14. Ng5 $2 {, allowing} h6 $1 {, which is to Black's advantage.}) 14... Nxc2 {Spielmann:Schwarz hat nun einen Bauern bei guter, gesicherter Stellung erobert und setzt diesen Vorteil in klassischer Weise zum Gewinn um. Es ist lehrreich zu sehen, wie Rubinstein geschickt Verteidigung mit Angriff zu vereinen weiß.} 15. Nxc2 ({Spielmann: Die Spielweise} 15. f5 Nxd4 16. fxg6 Nxe2 17. Ng5 {womit einige zuschauende Meister das weiße Spiel retten und sogar gewinnen wollten,} {scheitert nur an} Be6) 15... Qxc2 {Craig Pritchett: 'Black has an extra pawn and probably stands better. Spielmann, an outstanding attacking player, may have expected to obtain more compensation than actually appears to be present in the position. At any rate, he fails to achieve anything concrete. --- With his next move, White aims to play Nd4 without allowing Black's queen to pin the knight from c5.'} 16. b4 {Craig Pritchett: 'White angles to play Nd4 without allowing Black's queen to pin the knight from c5.' Kmoch: Er will d4 ziehen und die Fesselung c5 vermeiden.} ({Instead after} 16. Kg1 c6 17. b3 d5 18. Ne5 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Re8 {, Black stands well - Pinski.}) 16... a5 {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'Black still has development problems. With this move, he battles to open the a-file to get his rook on a8 into play quickly.'} 17. Ba3 ({Black's previous move was also aimed at dissuading} 17. Nd4 {, since after} Qa4 {he maintains an active pin against b5.}) 17... axb4 {Die Stärke seine Spiels liegt überhaupt nicht im Holzvorteil, sondern im Läuferpaar und dem Gegenangriff, den er nun bald einleiten wird.} ({Craig Pritchett: 'Not now' Auf Abenteuer wie} 17... Qa4 $2 {Craig Pritchett: 'because of' darf Schwarz sich nicht einlassen} 18. Ng5 $44 {Craig Pritchett: '!'} (18. Bb2 $44) 18... Be8 19. Rab1 {, and the attack has switched clearly to White.}) 18. Bxb4 Qf5 $17 (18... Rxa2 $2 19. Ng5 $14) 19. Qe3 h6 {Craig Pritchett: 'Having freed his rook on the queenside, Rubinstein turns to the kingside. This move is part of a typically far-sighted plan to open a second front on that flank. With his king safe and few weaknesses around it, Rubinstein wastes no time in driving forward on the kingside.'} ({Pinski's} 19... Ra4 {, and if} 20. Nd4 Qg4 21. Bc3 c5 22. Ne2 Bc6 {, is also good.}) 20. Rac1 {Craig Pritchett: '!?'} ({White might have preferred} 20. Nd4 Qd5 21. Bc3 {, but Black still seems to retain good chances after} c5 22. Nf3 Rg8 {.}) 20... Rg8 21. Kg1 g5 {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'Black has made decided progress on the kingside. His rook and g-pawn battery soon sets up serious threats which present White with difficulties in finding a defence.'} 22. Qc3 Rc8 23. fxg5 hxg5 24. Kh1 g4 25. Nd4 Qd5 $1 {Craig Pritchett: 'The black queen's powerful centralization on d5 secures Black's lines in all parts of the board, both in attack and defence.'} ({Craig Pritchett: 'It was still possible to go wrong by playing'} 25... Qg6 $2 {Craig Pritchett: ', allowing'} 26. Ba5 b6 27. Nc6+ Bxc6 28. Qxc6 $18 {Craig Pritchett: ', followed by Bxb6, and White wins.' Kmoch}) 26. Qe3 {Craig Pritchett: 'Black has seen no demons.'} ({Not} 26. Nc6+ $2 Bxc6 27. Qf6+ Kd7 {, and White loses.}) 26... g3 $1 {Craig Pritchett: 'Black's g-pawn just keeps thumping down the board. White now decides to allow Black to open the g-file.' Kmoch: Die weiße Königsstellung muß gelockert werden} 27. Bc3 Ra8 {Craig Pritchett: '!'} (27... gxh2 28. Nc6+ {Eine Kombination, dei zum ewige Schach führt.} Bxc6 29. Bf6+ Kd7 30. Qe7+ Bxe7 31. Rxe7+ {Craig Pritchett: ', and White has a draw by repetition.'} Kd8 32. Ree1+ {Kmoch}) 28. Nf3 ({Now if White plays} 28. h3 {, Black transposes into the line given in the note to White's 27th move after} c5 29. Nf3 Kc7 {. Craig Pritchett: ', and if'} 30. d4 c4 {.}) 28... gxh2 {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'With the g-file now open, Black's rook greedily eyes White's weak pawn on g2.'} 29. Bf6+ Kc8 30. Qc3 ({White might try} 30. Qe8+ Bxe8 31. Rxe8+ Kd7 32. Rxa8 {, but after} c5 33. Rd8+ Kc7 {, and if} 34. Be7 Rxg2 35. Kxg2 Bxe7 {, Black should win.}) 30... Qc5 31. Qd3 Qh5 32. Ne5 {Craig Pritchett: '!?' Craig Pritchett: 'White sets a last trap, but it fails to a fine reply.'} ({However, he also surely loses after} 32. Qc3 c6 {, with two extra black pawns and continuing pressure.}) 32... Rxg2 $19 {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'Crash! Black destroys White's final kingside pawn cover. Recall that Black's g-file plan began a long way back, with a modest looking step on his 19th move.'} ({Craig Pritchett: 'Black, of course, avoids'} 32... dxe5 $4 33. Rxe5 $18 Qg6 (33... Qg4 34. Re8+ $1 {and White mates.}) 34. Re8+ Bxe8 35. Qd8# {Spielmann/Kmoch}) 33. Kxg2 {Craig Pritchett: 'White must accept Black's sacrifice.'} ({After} 33. Nxd7 Rg1+ 34. Rxg1 hxg1=Q+ 35. Kxg1 Kxd7 36. Qc4 c6 {, Black controls all possible entry points into his position and has a winning advantage.}) 33... dxe5 {Spielmann:Es gibt keine Rettung für Weiß} 34. Rxe5 (34. Bxe5 h1=Q+ 35. Rxh1 Qxe5 {Spielmann}) (34. Kh1 Bd6 35. Qxd6 Qf3+ 36. Kxh2 Qf2+ 37. Kh1 Qxe1+ 38. Rxe1 cxd6 $19 {Spielmann}) 34... Qg4+ 35. Qg3 {Craig Pritchett: 'White's game is bust.'} ({Craig Pritchett: 'and is mated after'} 35. Kh1 {Craig Pritchett: '?'} Bc6+ 36. Rxc6 Qg1#) ({Craig Pritchett: 'He loses material after'} 35. Kxh2 Qf4+ 36. Qg3 ({or} 36. Kg1 Qxf6) 36... Qxd2+ ({Craig Pritchett: 'but not'} 36... Qxf6 $2 {Craig Pritchett: '??'} 37. Re8+ {Craig Pritchett: '!' Craig Pritchett: 'and White mates'} Bxe8 38. Qxc7#) 37. Qg2 Qf4+ (37... Qxc1 {,}) 38. Qg3 Rxa2+ $19) 35... Qxg3+ 36. Kxg3 Bd6 37. Kxh2 Rxa2 {Craig Pritchett: 'Black wins a third pawn for the exchange and his powerful bishops seal White's fate.'} 38. Kg1 Rxd2 39. Rh5 b6 40. Be5 Bc5+ 41. Kf1 Kb7 42. Bg3 Bb5+ 43. Ke1 Re2+ 44. Kd1 Rg2 45. Rc3 {Craig Pritchett: 'White could have resigned earlier.'} ({If} 45. Rg5 Rg1+ 46. Kd2 Rxc1 47. Kxc1 Be3+) ({or} 45. Rh3 Be2+ 46. Ke1 (46. Kd2 Bg4+) 46... Bb4+ {.}) 45... Be2+ 0-1


