1. e4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. a4 Rb8 {Is there anything better here?} ({If} 8... Be6 9. dxe5 Na5 10. Nd4 {and now} c5 $2 11. Nxe6 fxe6 {White can obtain an advantage;} {only by} 12. axb5 $14 ({for after} 12. Qg4 Qd7 {Black would reply to both} 13. f3 {with} (13. axb5 c4 $13) 13... c4 $13 {and the issue appears very doubtful.})) 9. axb5 axb5 10. dxe5 Be6 11. c3 Bc5 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. Bc2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Qd7 15. Qf4 Ne7 {So far Black's moves admit of no censure. But here the question arises, why Black failed to play} ({the strong move of.} 15... f6 {if} 16. Qh4 {Black would break the attack} {by} Bf5) 16. Nd4 {Now White obtains at least the advantage of two Bishops.} Bxd4 {Now the point c5 becomes very weak, so that the c-pawn is prevented from advancing and remains in want of support by the pieces.} ({if} 16... Ng6 17. Qg3 {and the f-pawn threatens to advance}) ({and if} 16... b4 $2 {White plays} 17. Nb3 {Black is already somewhat in difficulty.}) 17. Qxd4 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. Qc5 Ra8 20. Bf4 h5 21. h3 Ra4 $2 {And finally a blunder which costs a pawn. Schlechter was particularly indisposed at St.Petersburg.} 22. Rxa4 bxa4 23. Rd1 c6 24. Qa5 Qe7 25. Qxa4 Qh4 26. Rd3 d4 27. Rf3 ({Not} 27. g3 Qxh3 28. cxd4 {on account of} Nh4) 27... dxc3 28. bxc3 Ne7 29. Qe4 Nd5 30. c4 Nxf4 31. Rxf4 Qg5 32. e6 Qe7 33. Rxf7 Rxf7 34. exf7+ Qxf7 35. Qxc6 Kh7 36. Qe4+ g6 37. c5 Qd7 38. c6 Qd1+ 39. Kh2 Qd6+ 40. g3 Qc5 41. Kg2 Kg7 42. h4 Qd6 43. Qc4 Qc7 44. Qb5 {White's play in this game appears most accurate and sound.} 1-0


