{[%mdl 8256] Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: 'Round 9, played 3rd March 1927.''} 1. e4 Nc6 {Opening = B00_08 Nimzowitsch 1... c6 / Nimzowitsch 1... c6} 2. Nf3 e6 {Steve Giddins: '?!' '?!' Steve Giddins: 'The text leads to a kind of French structure, which was frequently Nimzowitsch's aim when playing his eponymous defence, but it must be admitted that this is probably not a very good French.'} ({Alternatives include} 2... d6 {(which was Tony Miles' favourite),}) ({as well as the move} 2... e5 {, transposing back into regular Open Games,}) ({whilst the creative Moscow IM Nicolai Vlassov has extensively analysed and tested the move} 2... d5 {, reaching a type of Scandinavian Defence.}) 3. d4 d5 4. e5 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: How is this any different from the positions reached via 2 d4 d5 3 Nc3 e6 4 e5? This can also be reached by the move order 1...e6 2 d4 d5 3 Nc3 Nc6 which has enjoyed some popularity of late, hasn't it? ANSWER: The difference here is that White has not committed his knight to c3. That deprives Black of the chance of ...Bb4, pinning the knight, and also allows White to reinforce his centre with c2-c3. QUESTION: So you don't like this variation for Black? ANSWER: Not especially. I am anyway a trifle suspicious of these very slow French Defence structures, where Black delays ...c5 and instead manoeuvres (a more pejorative commentator might say "grovels") around with stuff like ...b6 and ...Qd7, etc. The version in this game strikes me as even less attractive than usual. Players such as Nimzowitsch and Petrosian could handle the black side of such structures very well, but few other players are able to, and I really don't think they are objectively to be recommended. '} b6 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: So, what is the idea of this? The long diagonal does not look an attractive place for the bishop. ANSWER: Well, as we will see, Nimzowitsch intends to put the bishop on a6, in a bid to exchange off his bad bishop. Such manoeuvres are well known in these structures. QUESTION: It looks very slow! ANSWER: Yes, that is the main objection. Black's justification is that the position is blocked, so time is of less consequence than would be the case in an open position, but even so, it is all asking a bit much, I think. On the other hand, Black has few other sensible plans, and is already committed to the type of play which ensues. '} (4... Na5 $5 5. c3 b6) 5. c3 {last book move} Nce7 {Steve Giddins: '?!' '?!' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Another weird-looking move! ANSWER: Yes. Nimzowitsch was clearly in his element. We have already seen how much he liked such fanciful and 'mysterious' moves. It is all part of an elaborate scheme to establish a blockade on the square f5. QUESTION: I am not sure that is the first square I would have thought of in this position. ANSWER: Maybe not, but it is in total accordance with Nimzowitsch's theories about the pawn chain. The white pawn on e5 creates a 'qualitative majority' for White on the kingside. He wants to attack the base of the black chain, on e6, so the obvious long-term strategic advance for him to aim at is f4-f5. Ergo, the f5-square is the key point, which Black needs to try to control, and establish a blockade there. QUESTION: Deep stuff! ANSWER: Yes, although thanks to Nimzowitsch himself, 'every Russian schoolboy' nowadays understands that f4-f5 is a key idea in such positions. But, although his basic strategic understanding of the position cannot be faulted, even blockading on f5 is not a panacea for Black, who is terribly cramped, and has to create horrible dark-square weaknesses in order to achieve the desired light-square blockade.  ' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Another weird-looking move! ANSWER: Yes. Nimzowitsch was clearly in his element. We have already seen how much he liked such fanciful and 'mysterious' moves. It is all part of an elaborate scheme to establish a blockade on the square f5. QUESTION: I am not sure that is the first square I would have thought of in this position. ANSWER: Maybe not, but it is in total accordance with Nimzowitsch's theories about the pawn chain. The white pawn on e5 creates a 'qualitative majority' for White on the kingside. He wants to attack the base of the black chain, on e6, so the obvious long-term strategic advance for him to aim at is f4-f5. Ergo, the f5-square is the key point, which Black needs to try to control, and establish a blockade there. QUESTION: Deep stuff! ANSWER: Yes, although thanks to Nimzowitsch himself, 'every Russian schoolboy' nowadays understands that f4-f5 is a key idea in such positions. But, although his basic strategic understanding of the position cannot be faulted, even blockading on f5 is not a panacea for Black, who is terribly cramped, and has to create horrible dark-square weaknesses in order to achieve the desired light-square blockade.   Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!?''} 6. Bd3 a5 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Yet another non-developing move! But this one I guess I understand – he is preparing ...Ba6, yes? ANSWER: Indeed, which idea White takes immediate steps to prevent.  '} 7. Qe2 Nf5 8. h4 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: What is the idea?'} ({ANSWER: White wants to drive away the enemy knight with g2-g4, but the immediate} 8. g4 {allows the reply} Nh4 {, hence the preparatory text. However, the computer points out that even this may be good for White, thanks to a very nasty tactic:} 9. Nxh4 Qxh4 10. Nd2 {, and now I suspect Nimzowitsch (and Spielmann) assumed Black is doing well after the counterblow} h5 {. However, the demon silicon beast points out that White then has} 11. Nf3 {, and now} Qxg4 $2 (11... Qh3 {is a better try, although after} 12. gxh5 Qxh5 13. Rg1 {it is still not very nice for Black}) {fails to the queen-trap} 12. h3 Qg2 13. Rh2 {.}) 8... h5 {Steve Giddins: 'Black stops 9 g4, but at the cost of weakening g5. '} 9. Ng5 $11 (9. Bg5 {Steve Giddins: 'was also tempting.'} Nge7 $14) 9... g6 $14 {Steve Giddins: '?' '?' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: Isn't this part of his blockade plan on f5? ANSWER: Yes, but it is a really rather horrible move. Alekhine himself wrote that "Black's position could, perhaps, have withstood the eccentricities committed so far", but that this permanent weakening of f6 was too much.'} (9... Be7 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bd3 $11) ({Nimzowitsch himself later agreed, and recommended} 9... Nge7 10. Nd2 c5 {, although I still don't think much of Black's game after simply} 11. Ndf3 {.}) 10. Nd2 Nge7 ({The attempted larceny of} 10... Nxh4 $2 {is justly punished by} 11. Bb5+ $1 {e.g.} Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 (12... Qxd7 13. Rxh4) 13. Nxf7 {, winning.}) (10... c5) 11. Nf1 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: That looks a bit surprising. I assumed the knight would come to f3. ANSWER: That would also have been good, but Spielmann's move is very logical too. He intends to challenge the black blockade on f5, by playing f3 and g4, so his knight covers the g3-square in advance. ' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: That looks a bit surprising. I assumed the knight would come to f3. ANSWER: That would also have been good, but Spielmann's move is very logical too. He intends to challenge the black blockade on f5, by playing f3 and g4, so his knight covers the g3-square in advance.  Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: ' f3, g4''} c5 {Steve Giddins: 'Black finally makes this thematic French pawn break, exerting some pressure on the white centre. '} 12. f3 $15 (12. dxc5 $5 bxc5 13. b3 $11) 12... c4 $11 {Steve Giddins: '?' '?'} ({Steve Giddins: 'Black's last chance to obtain a vaguely playable position was'} 12... cxd4 13. g4 {Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!''} hxg4 14. fxg4 {Steve Giddins: ', and now the computer's suggestion'} Rxh4 (14... dxc3 $1 15. gxf5 Nxf5 16. bxc3 Qc7 {. QUESTION: So Black has sacrificed a piece? ANSWER: Yes, but he has two pawns, and has broken up the white position a good deal. The white king has no particularly safe home. QUESTION: So Black is OK here? ANSWER: I am not sure about that. White is still better after} 17. Bd2 {, for example, but Black has some play and some practical chances.}) (14... Nh6 15. cxd4 {is just positionally great for White, who has refuted the attempted kingside blockade plan,}) ({whilst} 14... Nxh4 $2 15. Qf2 {loses a piece for Black Steve Giddins: 'loses a piece for Black Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '+-''}) 15. Rxh4 Nxh4 $16) 13. Bc2 {Steve Giddins: 'Now the character of the game has changed completely from the line given in the previous note. The position remains closed, but Black has no real counterplay at all. QUESTION: What is the problem? ANSWER: The move 12...c4 has lifted the pressure from White's centre, which is now very securely defended, and he has a free hand on the kingside. QUESTION: But Black can play ...b5-b4, can't he, with a queenside counterattack? ANSWER: Yes, but that is little more than a pin-prick for White. Black cannot bring any extra pressure to bear against c3, which is anyway easy to defend. Meanwhile, Black has terrible problems on the kingside. QUESTION: So your verdict would be 'Don't try this at home'? ANSWER: Definitely. If pressed for a judgement, I would say Black is strategically lost. '} b5 14. g4 Ng7 ({Not} 14... hxg4 $2 15. fxg4 Rxh4 ({or} 15... Nxh4 16. Qf2) 16. Rxh4 Nxh4 17. Qf2 {and wins}) {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: This looks like another typically bizarre Nimzowitsch position! ANSWER: Yes, one does not see too many fianchettoed knights. But that is for a good reason – this position is just dreadful for Black. His only hope is that the fairly blocked nature of the position will make it hard for White to break through. '} 15. Ng3 {Steve Giddins: '!?' '!?'} ({Logical enough, although the computer is very keen on the plan of bringing the white queen to f4:} 15. Qd2 Nc6 16. Qf4 {, and after} Qe7 17. Bd2 {Black is appallingly tied up. Admittedly, White still has to break through, though.}) 15... Nc6 16. Qg2 {Steve Giddins: 'It was still possible to revert to the plan of bringing the queen to f4, but Spielmann has another idea. He intends to break in down the g-file, with the aid of a sacrifice on f7. QUESTION: Was that really necessary? ANSWER: Maybe not, but a sacrifice is the usual way to deal with these blocked structures. Once White has all his pieces mobilized, his massive space advantage usually allows him to transfer pieces to the critical sector of the board much more readily than Black is able to do, suffering as he does with such a cramped position, and lacking lines of communication for his pieces. As the later notes will show, Spielmann's plan was perfectly correct and should have won.  '} Be7 (16... Ra7 17. gxh5 Nxh5 18. Nxh5 Rxh5 19. Nxf7 Rxf7 20. Bxg6 Rxh4 21. Bxf7+ Kxf7 22. Rg1) 17. gxh5 gxh5 (17... Nxh5 {Steve Giddins: '?' '?'} 18. Nxf7 $1 (18. Nxh5 Rxh5 {allows an immediate winning breakthrough with} 19. Nxf7 {. Steve Giddins: '. Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '+-''}) 18... Kxf7 19. Bxg6+ Kf8 20. Nxh5 (20. Bxh5 $6 Bxh4 21. Kd1 Ra7 $16) 20... Bxh4+ 21. Kf1 Nxd4 22. cxd4 $18) 18. Rg1 (18. Nh7 Bxh4 19. Rxh4 $1 Qxh4 20. Bg5 $18) 18... Ra7 19. Nxf7 $4 $19 {Steve Giddins: '!?' '!?' Steve Giddins: 'The critical moment of the game has been reached.'} (19. Qd2 $142 $14) ({The text is objectively good enough to win, as the following note shows, but Alekhine's suggestion of one more preparatory move with} 19. Ke2 {was even better. QUESTION: Why is that? ANSWER: The king move serves two purposes. Firstly, it gets the king out of the way of a check from h4 (we will see the move ...Bxh4+ cropping up in various of the subsequent variations), and it clears the back rank, in anticipation of the queen's rook being able to swing over to the kingside. QUESTION: But presumably Spielmann was afraid of giving Black extra time to arrange his defences. Can't he make profitable use of the tempo gained? ANSWER: Analysis suggests not. 20 Nxf7 is now a devastating threat, so the obvious thing to do is to cover f7, by means of Steve Giddins: 'was even better. QUESTION: Why is that? ANSWER: The king move serves two purposes. Firstly, it gets the king out of the way of a check from h4 (we will see the move ...Bxh4+ cropping up in various of the subsequent variations), and it clears the back rank, in anticipation of the queen's rook being able to swing over to the kingside. QUESTION: But presumably Spielmann was afraid of giving Black extra time to arrange his defences. Can't he make profitable use of the tempo gained? ANSWER: Analysis suggests not. 20 Nxf7 is now a devastating threat, so the obvious thing to do is to cover f7, by means of Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!''} Bf8 {. However, then} 20. Nh7 $1 {threatens Nf6+ and/or Bh6 and Nxf8. Black is helpless, as the computer confirms:} Kd7 21. Bh6 Kc7 22. Nf1 {(the threat is 23 Nxf8, simply winning a piece, and Black is so helplessly cramped and tied up that he has no way to avoid the loss of material)} Nf5 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Nxf8 Qxf8 25. Bxf5 exf5 26. Qg5 {and White has an extra exchange and still crushing pressure on the dark squares.}) 19... Kxf7 20. Nxh5 {Threatening mate... how? Steve Giddins: '?' '?' Steve Giddins: 'This second piece sacrifice is a step too far, however. Spielmann had probably missed Black's 23rd move.'} ({Alekhine suggested various possible alternatives for White, one of which is} 20. Ne4 $1 {, which the computer confirms is the strongest, and just wins by force:} Bxh4+ {(now we see why the preparatory 19 Ke2 would have been useful, so this move does not come with check, but White is winning anyway)} 21. Ke2 Kg8 ({or} 21... Ne8 22. Nd6+ Ke7 23. Qh3 {and wins}) 22. Nd6 Qf8 ({if} 22... Rc7 23. Qg6 {with ideas of Bh6 or even Ne8; after} Qf8 24. Bh6 {the attack is crushing: the threats include Ne8 and Rg2 followed by Rag1}) 23. Qh3 Be7 (23... Bd8 24. Nxc8) 24. Rxg7+ $1 Qxg7 25. Nxc8 Rc7 26. Qxe6+ Qf7 27. Nxe7+ Nxe7 28. Qb6 {and White has material equality (two pawns for the exchange), and still a raging attack, with Be3 and Rg1 coming.}) ({Another Alekhine suggestion was} 20. Ne2 {, after which Keene gives the variation} Bxh4+ 21. Kd1 Kg8 $2 ({however, in this line, Fritz points out that Black is hanging on after} 21... Qg8 {, so 20 Ne2 is not so good}) 22. Nf4 Rf7 23. Ng6 Be7 24. Nxh8 Kxh8 25. Qg6 {, winning. Steve Giddins: ', winning. Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '+-!''}) (20. Bg6+) (20. Nf5) 20... Bxh4+ $1 (20... Nxh5 $4 21. Qg6+ Kf8 22. Bh6+ Ng7 23. Bxg7+ Kg8 24. Bh6#) (20... Rxh5 $4 21. Qxg7+ Ke8 22. Bg6+ Kd7 23. Bxh5 $18) 21. Ke2 Nxh5 (21... Rxh5 $4 22. Qxg7+ Ke8 23. Bg6+ Rf7 24. Qxf7#) 22. Bg6+ Ke7 23. Bxh5 {The mate threat is Qg7} Kd7 {Steve Giddins: '!!' '!!' Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!''} ({Steve Giddins: 'No doubt a very unpleasant shock for Spielmann, who had presumably only reckoned on'} 23... Rxh5 $6 24. Qg7+ Ke8 25. Qg8+ (25. Qg6+ {, although even here, things are still fairly unclear after} Kd7 26. Qxh5 Be7 {.}) 25... Kd7 26. Qf7+ Be7 27. Qxh5 $11) 24. Qg7+ Be7 25. Bf7 {Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: ' 26.Bxe6+ Kxe6 27.Qg4+ Kf7 28.Qg6+ Kf8 29.Bh6+''} Rh2+ (25... Qf8 26. Qxf8 Bxf8 27. Be3 $19) 26. Kd1 Kc7 (26... Qf8 {was also winning, but at most points from now on, Black had other equally good choices than the moves played. The rest does not really require detailed commentary.}) 27. Bf4 $2 (27. b3 $142 $19) 27... Rxb2 28. Qh7 Kb6 29. Rg8 Qc7 30. Qh8 (30. Qh3 Bd8 31. Rg7 Bf6 $19) 30... Nd8 (30... Ba3 $5 31. Be8 Qh7 32. Qxh7 Rxh7 33. Rg1 $19) 31. Bg6 Rg2 $17 (31... Bd7 $142 $5 $19) 32. Qh1 Rxg6 $1 {Steve Giddins: 'Black gives back some of his extra material, to eliminate one of the white attacking pieces. This is not the only way to win, but is a typical defensive technique, of course. '} 33. Rxg6 b4 (33... Ba3 34. Bc1 Qf7 35. Qg2 $17) 34. Rg7 (34. Rb1 Qd7 35. Qg2 Qa4+ 36. Qc2 Qxc2+ 37. Kxc2 Nc6 $17) 34... Qc6 (34... bxc3 35. Bg5 Nc6 36. Bxe7 c2+ 37. Kc1 Nxe7 38. Kxc2 $19) 35. Qh8 $19 (35. Rg2 Qa4+ 36. Rc2 bxc3 37. Rb1+ Ka6 $19) 35... Qa4+ (35... bxc3 36. Rxe7 Rxe7 37. Qxd8+ Qc7 38. Qxc7+ Kxc7 39. Bg3 $17) 36. Ke1 Nc6 {Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!''} (36... bxc3 $4 37. Rxe7 Rd7 38. Bg5 $18) 37. Qxc8 $2 {Steve Giddins: 'Allowing a decisive counterattack, but it really does not matter anymore. White could and should just resign. '} (37. Rg2 $142 Kc7 38. Rc1 $19) 37... Bh4+ 38. Bg3 (38. Rg3 Qc2 39. Rd1 Qxc3+ 40. Ke2 $19) 38... Rxg7 39. Bxh4 Qc2 $1 {Do you see the mate threat? Steve Giddins: 'Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '!''} (39... Rg1+ 40. Kf2 Rxa1 41. Bd8+ $1 Nxd8 42. Qxd8+ $11) 40. Bd8+ Nxd8 41. Qb8+ ({Steve Giddins: 'He runs out of checks at once after'} 41. Qxd8+ Kb7 {Steve Giddins: '.' Steve Giddins: '. Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '-+!''} 42. Qe7+ Rxe7 43. Rc1 Qxc1+ 44. Ke2 Rh7 45. Kf2 Rh2+ 46. Kg3 Qg1+ 47. Kf4 Rh4#) 41... Nb7 {Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: But surely Nimzowitsch was just lucky here, wasn't he? He was outplayed and had a lost position, only for his opponent to miss a tactic and sacrifice unsoundly. ANSWER: That is all true, but this is in many ways typical of the 'provocation' style, of which Nimzowitsch was fond. His opening play was deliberately very risky and provocative, tempting his opponent to attack and to burn his boats in the process. It is true that, this time, Nimzowitsch went a bit far, and objectively was losing, but that is always an inherent risk with such an approach. Other defenders, who have adopted a similar approach, include the young Korchnoi, and he too would lose a few games that way, and an even greater number of post-mortems, where his opponents would succeed in showing that they should have won. However, 'should haves' and 'could haves' do not yield even a fraction of a point in the tournament table, and overall, the Nimzowitschs and Korchnois won an awful lot more games as Black than they would have done with a correct, equalizing approach.' Steve Giddins: 'QUESTION: But surely Nimzowitsch was just lucky here, wasn't he? He was outplayed and had a lost position, only for his opponent to miss a tactic and sacrifice unsoundly. ANSWER: That is all true, but this is in many ways typical of the 'provocation' style, of which Nimzowitsch was fond. His opening play was deliberately very risky and provocative, tempting his opponent to attack and to burn his boats in the process. It is true that, this time, Nimzowitsch went a bit far, and objectively was losing, but that is always an inherent risk with such an approach. Other defenders, who have adopted a similar approach, include the young Korchnoi, and he too would lose a few games that way, and an even greater number of post-mortems, where his opponents would succeed in showing that they should have won. However, 'should haves' and 'could haves' do not yield even a fraction of a point in the tournament table, and overall, the Nimzowitschs and Korchnois won an awful lot more games as Black than they would have done with a correct, equalizing approach. Nimzowitsch/Alekhine: '(Source: "New York 1927" tmt book.)''} (41... Nb7 42. Qxb7+ Kxb7 43. Kf1 Rg2 44. cxb4 Qe2#) 0-1


