{C56: Two Knights: 4 d4 exd4 5 0-0 xe4 Sources: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of Chess, pp. 6-7; Marco & Schlechter (ed. Robert Sherwood), Karlsbad 1907 International Chess Tournament, pp. 372-373. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted.  The feature of the following beautiful game is the thorough manner in which White takes advantage of the e-file, which he opens at the cost of the temporary sacrifice of a pawn (8. 0-0), and finally controls at the cost of another pawn (19. d6). His forces penetrate into the hostile position (18. e7, 25. fe7, and 29.e7), with the most damaging results.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 d6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb6 7. h3 {1-0 Leonhardt,P-Maroczy,G Karlsbad-01 International Masters 1907 (9) As in reply to 7.e3, or 7.c3, Black's 7 .... g4 might prove irksome, White decides to sacrifice a tempo in his development in order to eliminate this threat once and for all. Marco: In his famous game against Maroczy, Leonhardt played 7.c3 followed by castling. Spielmann's move h2-h3, preventing ....g4 first, is also good.} {7....} Nf6 8. O-O ({If} 8. Nc3 {there follows the well-known simplification:} Nxe4 9. Nxe4 ({or} 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Nxe4 Re8 {artificial castling, advantageous in this case;}) (9. Qe2 O-O) 9... d5 {For this reason White gives up the threatened pawn for the sake of an attack.}) 8... Nxe4 9. Re1 O-O ({Marco: Better is} 9... d5 10. Bxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc3 Qh5 12. Nxe4 ({or} 12. Rxe4+ Be6 13. d5 O-O-O 14. Bg5 f6 ({not} 14... Rd7 {due to} 15. Qb3 Na5 16. Qa4 Bf5 17. Rh4 Qg6 18. b4) 15. Rxe6 fxg5) 12... O-O 13. Ng3 Qg6) 10. Rxe4 d5 11. Bg5 {White gains an important tempo by this intermediary manoeuvre, as Black could not very well reply 11.... f6, on account of 12. b3, fxg5; 13. c3, with advantage to White. 11....} Qd6 $146 12. Bxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Rb6d4,Rc6d4,Rd5d4,Gd1d4,Ge4d4,Gf3d4]} 13. Nc3 Qd7 14. d5 {Although isolated, this centre pawn assumes the role of a blockader. 14....} f6 15. Be3 Nd8 {In order to control the square at e-6,} ({for if} 15... Ne7 {there follows} 16. Bxb6 axb6 17. Qb3 Kh8 18. Nd4 {with many threats.}) 16. Bxb6 $18 axb6 17. Qe2 {Increasing the pressure on the e-file. 17....} Nf7 18. Re7 Qd8 {With the counter-threat 19....e5.} 19. d6 {A vacating sacrifice. Marco: White offers a pawn so that he does not have to relinquish the rook's position on e7. Back was threatening 19....Ne5. On 19.b5, simply 19....d7 would follow. 19....} Nxd6 {A crucial moment.} ({It is obvious that after} 19... Qxd6 20. Nb5 ({as also} 20. Rd1 {) is to White's advantage.})) ({Similarly, if} 19... c6 {the following beautiful continuation secures White an advantage in material:} 20. d7 Bxd7 21. Rd1 Ne5 22. Rdxd7 Nxd7 23. Qe6+ Kh8 24. Rxd7) ({Less clear is the ultimate result of} 19... cxd6 {; e.g.} 20. Nb5 ({the most logical move is} 20. Re3 {anticipating future weaknesses on Black's queen side}) 20... Ra5 21. Rd1 Ne5 {; threatening 22 .... xe5.}) 20. Nd5 Rf7 21. Re1 Bd7 22. Nh4 {This knight wishes even to surpass its companion in usefulness. 22....} Ra5 {Instead of thus relinquishing the greatest possible control of his first rank, Black would have done better to play 22 .... c6.} 23. Rxf7 Nxf7 24. Nf5 { A tactical finesse which is to bring yet another piece into the firing line: (24.... xf5 25. e8+ xe8 26. xe8#). Marco: A charming position. Black cannot capture either of the attacked knights. Spielmann plays the final attack very forcefully and beautifully. 24....} Ne5 {Ordre, contre-ordre, désordre. The Black king should have looked after his own defence by 24 .... f8.} 25. Nfe7+ Kh8 26. b4 Ra8 27. f4 Ng6 ({Sherwood: This was a serious error. With} 27... Nc6 {Blacks holds with little difficulty.}) 28. Nxg6+ hxg6 29. Ne7 Qe8 ({Black's precarious situation is well illustrated also in the following variation:} 29... Be8 30. Rd1 {and the black Queen has only one pitiful retreat, namely 30....} Qb8 {after which follows:} 31. Qg4 {threatening 32. h4#.}) 30. Qf2 g5 31. fxg5 fxg5 {In order to save the mate, Black must already leave corpses by the way.} 32. Qd2 b5 33. Qxg5 Ra6 34. Re4 Rh6 ({Black has no valid defence, e.g.} 34... Qf7 35. Rh4+ Rh6 36. Rxh6+ gxh6 37. Qxh6+ Qh7 38. Ng6+ ({or} 38. Qf8+ {with mate to follow}) 38... Kg8 39. Qf8#) 35. Nf5 Qg6 ({Saving the exchange, but losing a piece. As, however, neither 35.... xe4 nor 35.... e6 is feasible (because of 36.xg7#), Black disdains the continuation} 35... Qf8 36. Nxh6 gxh6 {; with a slightly prolonged agony.}) 36. Qd8+ ({If} 36. Nxh6 {, Black plays, not 36 .... xg5 (because of 37. f7+ and xg5), but 36....} Qxe4 {; and Black is safe!}) 36... Kh7 37. Qxd7 Rh5 38. Rg4 Rg5 {[#]} 39. Rh4+ {Black Resigns.} 1-0


