1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 {(Simpler than ...f6.)} 4. Ne2 ({More natural would be} 4. Nf3) 4... e6 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h5 7. Be2 Be7 ({Thus White's maneuver is justified. But Black could have played better, namely} 7... Nb4 8. Na3 c5 9. c3 Nc6 {[%csl Yc6,Yd4,Yd5,Ye5] and White's efforts against Black's h-pawn appear to be excessive in view of the serious situation in the center.}) 8. Bxh5 Bxh5 9. Nxh5 g6 10. Nf4 Rxh4 11. Rxh4 Bxh4 12. Qd3 (12. Qd3 {Preventing} Bg5 {as then} 13. Nxe6 {would win.}) 12... Nge7 $1 13. g3 Nf5 14. gxh4 Nfxd4 ({There is now a double threat, namely} 14... Nfxd4 15. Z0 Nb4 ({and} 15... Nxe5 16. Qxd4 Nf3+ {a neat two-fold turn.}) 16. Qxd4 Nxc2+) 15. Na3 Qxh4 ({Simpler would be} 15... Nxe5 16. Qh3 Ndf3+ 17. Kf1 Qxh4 {with a promising ending, but Black wished to avoid the exchange of Queens.}) 16. Qh3 {(In order to force the exchange.)} Qg5 (16... Qg5 {With the idea} 17. Qh8+ Kd7 18. Qxa8 Qg1+ 19. Kd2 Qxf2+ 20. Kc3 Nb3 $3 {Nevertheless 16...Qxh3 was necessary.} ({after the game they found the dual} 20... Nf3)) 17. Be3 ({But now} 17. Nd3 {could have been played to White's advantage, e.g.} Qg1+ 18. Kd2 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Qxf2+ {would be insufficient.}) ({as would be the other possible continuation} 17. Nd3 Qg1+ 18. Kd2 Kd7 19. Nc5+ ({not} 19. c3 {because of} Rh8 20. Qxh8 Qg5+ {with perpetual check}) 19... Ke7 20. Qh4+ Ke8 ({or} 20... g5 21. Qg3) 21. Qh8+ Ke7 22. Qf6+ Kf8 {and} 23. c3) 17... Qg1+ 18. Qf1 Nf3+ 19. Ke2 Nfd4+ 20. Kd2 Nf3+ 21. Ke2 Ncd4+ 22. Kd3 {(Fatal.)} ({For better or worse, White should have embarked upon} 22. Bxd4 Nxd4+ 23. Kd3 Qg5 {although his position then would scarecely have been enviable.}) 22... Qg5 23. Qh3 Qxe5 24. Rf1 O-O-O 25. b3 b5 26. Nxb5 Qe4+ 27. Kc3 Qxc2+ 28. Kb4 c5+ {White resigns. Here I close this book and bid farewell to my readers.} 0-1


