1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bf4 Bf5 {(An innovation.)} 6. Nf3 e6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nbd2 f6 {(Secures his e5 square and prepares for a general advance on the Kingside. A strategic diversion here is justified, as his own center appears reasonably secure, for his e6 is well covered and the diagonal f5-b1 makes a pretty picture. We have emphasized already more than once that a flank attack, when your own center is insecure, is inadmissible.)} 9. Be2 ({Here} 9. c4 {was indicated, for example} Bb4 ({Or} 9... Nb4 10. Rc1 {and White has nothing to fear.}) 10. cxd5 exd5 {with an even game.}) 9... g5 10. Bg3 h5 11. h3 Nge7 12. O-O ({Now} 12. c4 {would no longer improve matters. For example} dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nd5 {with a strong Knight in the center; nevertheless, this line was preferable to the text.}) 12... Bh6 13. Ne1 g4 14. Qd1 Bxd2 {(This wins a pawn.)} 15. Qxd2 gxh3 16. Nd3 b6 17. Rfe1 h4 18. Bh2 Kf7 ({Not} 18... O-O-O {because of} 19. Nc5 $1 bxc5 20. Ba6+ Qb7 21. Bxb7+ {Other moves also lose.}) 19. g4 hxg3 20. Bxg3 h2+ 21. Kg2 Be4+ ({The win was more clearly demonstrated as follows:} 21... e5 22. dxe5 Be4+ 23. f3 Rag8 24. e6+ ({Or} 24. Qf4 Nf5 25. fxe4 Nxg3 26. Qxf6+ Ke8 27. e6 h1=Q+ 28. Rxh1 Nxh1+ {and wins.}) 24... Qxe6 25. Nf4 Qg4 $1) 22. Bf3 ({With} 22. f3 {White could have held out a little longer.}) 22... Nf5 $1 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Nf4 ({If} 24. Rxe4 {then} Qd5) 24... e5 25. Ne2 Nh4+ 26. Bxh4 Qg4+ {And mate in a few moves.} 0-1


