{The game that follows was played at the same tournament as the preceding one, but was played in a more 'energetic style'. But it is only at first glance that this style seems related to the style that brought me so many disappointments (Barmen!). Analysing my play in this game attentively produces a satisfying impression (see for instance my note to Black's fourth move).} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 3. exd5 c6 {An innovation I invented.} 4. Qf3 (4. Nc3 {, then} exf4 5. Nf3 cxd5 {with equal chances.}) 4... exf4 {Straight after the game ended I demonstrated this variation:} (4... cxd5 5. fxe5 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bc5 7. c3 Bxg1 8. Rxg1 Qb6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. d4 Ba6 {and White has weak white squares.   From this example, as from the endgame with E. Cohn, it is apparent that the strategy of play according to the points of the specified colour, which at that time was still unknown territory, was not a secret for me.}) 5. dxc6 Nxc6 6. Bb5 Nf6 {Black bravely offers a pawn for better development.} 7. d4 Bd7 8. Ne2 {If} (8. c3 $1 {, then} Qb6) 8... Qb6 9. Qd3 Bd6 10. c4 O-O $1 {Evidently the completely correct sacrifice of a piece.} 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. c5 Bxc5 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Bxf4 Rfe8 { With the triple threat of ...Bd5, ...Bxg2 and ...Rxe2+.} 15. Nbc3 Bxg2 {A pawn won back from sacrificed material that is calm and executed with sober realism.} 16. O-O-O Bxh1 17. Rxh1 Rad8 {With a strong attack.} 18. Qc2 {If} (18. Qf3 b5 19. Kb1 b4 20. Nd1 Rxe2 21. Qxe2 Qf5+ {, and wins.}) 18... Nd5 {With the threat of 19...Nb4 20.Qb3 Rxe2.} 19. Bd2 {If} (19. Nxd5 Qxc2+ 20. Kxc2 Rxe2+ 21. Kd3 Rxb2 22. Kd4 (22. Kc3) 22... Rxa2 {with an easy win.}) 19... Nb4 20. Qd1 Nd3+ 21. Kb1 Nf2 {White resigned. (Source: How I Became a Grandmaster. The Chess-Player's Library 1929.)} 0-1


