1. e4 {Lachaga: Trebitsch Gedenkturniere Wien 1907-1938 und Internationales Schachmeisterturnier Wien 1935. S.38 [Becker]} e6 {The French Defence, with several objects in view: 1) to prevent White from dictating the opening. After the conventional reply 1 ... e5 White can play the Ruy Lopez, the Giuoco Piano, the Scotch, the Vienna Game or a dangerous gambit of some sort.  2) Black's cramped position may tempt White into a disastrous premature attack. 3) the pawn at E6 supports an advance by 2 ... d5, an attack on the E-pawn which might wrest (arrancar, puxar) the initiative.} 2. d4 {The second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black challenges the centre.} 3. Nc3 {The knight develops to its proper square, protects the E-pawn, and bears down on D5.} Nf6 {Black brings his own knight to its strongest position with gain of time - a further attack on the E4-pawn.} 4. exd5 {Many players prefer to add to the pressure by 4. Bg5 (which develops a piece and renders one of the enemy's impotent) rather than exchange pawns, which relaxes the tension. Spielmann, who likes wide-open positions, clears away a couple of pawns to give his pieces more room for their activities. Which move is better? Which should you play? The answer is: play the move that you like, the one that best suits your style and temperament. If you are a careful, cautious player who knows the full value of a pawn - that each one is a potential queen, and that the loss of a pawn may be the loss of the game - stick to 4. Bg5 and the openings of positional chess, the Ruy Lopez, the Queen's Pawn openings, the Reti and the English. On the other hand, if you prefer daring, adventurous chess, and a pawn is simply a barrier to the sweeping onrush of an attack by your pieces, play openings which allow scope for your imagination, the Evans, Danish, King's and other gambits. The best openings to play are the ones you are most at home in.} (4. Bg5 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. c3 $11) 4... exd5 {Better than taking with the knight. Black keeps a pawn in the centre and frees his C8-bishop.} 5. Bg5 {White pins the knight and threatens to break up Black's game by 6. Bxf6 gxf6 (6 ... Qxf6 loses the D5-pawn), when Black is left with a weak doubled pawn.} Be7 {The simplest way of unpinning the knight. Moving the bishop only one square may not seem much of a move, but it complies with the first law of rapid development: Get your pieces off the back rank!} 6. Bd3 {This bishop's stand is aggressive, especially against kingside castling.} Nc6 {This knight's debut is even more menacing, as it threatens to take the D-pawn.} 7. Nge2 {After the customary development 7. Nf3, Black pins the knight by 7 .... Bg4 and again threatens the D-pawn. White could save the pawn, for instance by 8. Be2, but would lose the initiative. After the text-move, if Black pins the knight by 7 .... Bg4, 8. f3 repels the bishop and causes it to lose time retreating.} Nb4 {Intending to get rid of a dangerous enemy piece (Bd3) and also to assure himself of a little advantage in keeping both his bishops.} 8. Ng3 {Now we see another reason for developing the knight to E2. White wants to anchor a piece at F5, a dominating position for a knight or a bishop. A piece need do no more than just stand there and look menacing to rattle the opponent.} Nxd3+ {Mission accomplished. Black has a slight technical superiority in retaining two long-range bishops against White's knight and bishop, but ...} 9. Qxd3 {... at the cost of a loss of time. Black has made three moves with the knight to exchange it for a bishop that moved only once. More than that, his knight came off the board completely, while the bishop left a piece in its place. The result is that White has four active pieces in play against two of Black's. White is also prepared to castle on either side and mobilize both rooks quickly. Whatever advantage exists is therefore White's.} g6 $2 {(1.00)  This pawn move prevents White from placing his knight at F5, but it creates an organic weakness in Black's position, one that is irremediable. The squares F6 and H6, no longer guarded by the pawn, are weak and remain so permanently. Notice that the pawn was induced but not forced to move forward. The mere threat of an inroad by the knight was enough to influence Black to make a natural preventive move. It is the sort of move nine out of ten players make automatically in similar situations, which is why it is important to know how to exploit its defects, for no move is weak unless proper advantage is taken of its flaws.} (9... O-O $142 {'='} 10. O-O c6 11. Rfe1 Re8 $11) 10. O-O c6 {'?!' (1.50) Strengthens Black's pawn-centre and opens another avenue for his queen.} (10... h6 {(0.50)} 11. Bf4 c6 12. Rfe1 Be6 13. Re2 Qd7 {(0.30)}) 11. Rae1 {'!'  White seizes the only open file (since rooks belong on open files or on files likely to be opened) and pins the bishop. It is worth noting that a pinned piece not only is unable to move but is also powerless to capture. It does not protect any other pieces, since it is completely paralysed. Hence it follows that not only is the bishop immobilized and in danger of its life (as it may be attacked again and again) but the knight that depends on it for protection is no longer secure. Briefly, Black is now threatened with loss of a piece by 12. Bxf6.} O-O {'?' (2.40)  The king takes refuge in flight, incidentally unpinning the bishop and preserving his knight. Spielmann's strategy to this point and the decisive combination that follows would have pleased Lasker, who once said, "In the beginning of the game ignore the search for combinations, abstain from violent moves. Aim for small advantages, accumulate them, and only after having attained these ends search for the combination - and then with all the power of will and intellect, because then the combination must exist, however deeply hidden." A glance shows that White has achieved the requisite positional superiority. If there is a combination to be evolved, it must be now, before Black has time to reorganize his pieces for defence. Now, while he has five pieces actively in play against two of Black's. Now, while he has an open file ... The combination must be there! Here is White's line of reasoning: Black's advance of the G-pawn has deprived the knight of stable support. It is still guarded by two pieces, but if the bishop were not there it would be defended only once. In fact, if the bishop were not there, the knight would be pinned and subject to an enduring attack. The bishop appears in both equations. Obviously the bishop must be destroyed! And at once, before Black has time for 12 ... Be6!} (11... Be6 {(1.20)} 12. f4 Rg8 13. Rf3 Qd7 14. Bh4 O-O-O 15. f5 g5 16. fxe6 fxe6 17. Bxg5 Rxg5 18. Qe3 Ng4 19. Qxe6 Qxe6 20. Rxe6 Kd7 21. Re1 Bd6 22. Rf7+ Kc8 23. Re6 Rg6 24. Rxg6 hxg6 {(0.55)}) 12. Rxe7 $1 $16 {'!'} Qxe7 {Black must recapture, leaving the knight pinned and a fine target for further attack.} 13. Qf3 {Putting pressure on the pinned piece, and threatening to take the knight.} Kg7 {'?'} (13... Bg4 14. Qf4 Kg7 15. f3 Be6 (15... Bd7 16. Nce4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Nd5 18. Nh5+ Kh8 (18... gxh5 $2 19. Qg3 Bg4 20. Bxe7 Nxe7 21. Qe5+ f6 22. Qxe7+ Rf7 23. Qc5 {(5.50)}) 19. exd5 f6 20. Bxf6+ Rxf6 21. Qxf6+ Qxf6 22. Nxf6 Bf5 23. g4 Kg7 24. gxf5 Kxf6 25. fxg6+ Kxg6 26. dxc6 bxc6 {(3.60)}) 16. Nce4 dxe4 17. fxe4 $18) (13... Bf5 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Qg3 {threatening mate by 16. Bxf6#} Kg7 {'?'} (15... Ne4 $1 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Be7+ Qg4 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Re1 {(1.20)}) (15... Kh8 16. Qh4 Kg7 17. Qh6+ Kg8 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 {(15.00)}) 16. Bxf6+ Kxf6 17. Qh4+ Ke6 {'?'} (17... Kg7 18. Qxe7 {(15.00)}) 18. Re1+ $18 Kd7 19. Qxe7+ {winning} Kc8 20. Qxf8+ Kc7 21. Qxa8) (13... Qd6 14. Bxf6 Bg4 15. Qxg4 Qxf6 16. Nd1 Rae8 17. Ne3 {(2.00)}) 14. Nce4 {'!'  White must keep hammering at the pinned knight, no matter how many brilliant moves he has to find! Again, White's immediate threat is simple: 15. Bxf6+, winning instantaneously.} dxe4 15. Nxe4 $18 {Three pieces now attack the helpless knight. White now threatens 16. Bxf6+, followed by 17. Bxe7.} Qe6 {(13.00) With this move, Black saves the queen - he is still ahead in material -, but has a lost game, as White's pieces will insinuate themselves along the dark squares to get at the king.} (15... Nxe4 {(8.00)} 16. Bxe7 Re8 17. Qxe4 Bf5 18. Qh4 h6 19. Qf6+ Kg8 20. Re1 {(9.00)}) (15... Qxe4 {(8.00) - in this line, notice how White screws his pieces firmly into the two holes in Black's position, F6 and H6, the squares no longer guarded by the G-pawn after its advance.} 16. Qxf6+ (16. Bxf6+ {removing the protector of the queen} Kg8 17. Qxe4) 16... Kg8 17. Bh6) 16. Bxf6+ {White regains a piece and limits Black's king to two moves.} Kg8 (16... Kh6 17. Qf4+ Kh5 18. Qh4#) 17. Qf4 {Threatening a final invasion at H6 followed by mate at G7 - triumph on the dark squares. Powerless to prevent mate, Black resigned.} Qg4 (17... Qxf6 18. Nxf6+ Kg7 19. Qe5 Be6 20. Ne8+ Kh6 (20... Kg8 21. Qg7#) 21. Qg7+ Kh5 22. Nf6+ Kg5 23. f4+ Kh4 24. Qh6#) 18. Qh6 c5 19. Qg7# 1-0


