{[%evp 0,55,29,29,29,29,84,39,45,33,14,14,11,7,28,1,6,6,14,-16,-4,-6,43,-2,-10,-10,-19,-4,7,-4,10,32,31,77,56,98,58,82,131,124,138,236,229,270,270,270,266,287,287,272,272,278,274,242,278,267,480,555] Quelle: Lars Bo Hansen, "Foundations of Chess Strategy", Gambit 2005, p. 70 ff.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4 e6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bd3 (6. a3) (6. cxd5) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 a6 8. O-O b5 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. a4 c4 $2 {Black has given up the centre with his 6th move, and consequently he now places the emphasis of his play on the queenside - a weighty strategic mistake. In the opening or at least in the early middlegame the main battle takes place in the centre, and who is stronger here will emerge with a positional advantage and attack. (Tarrasch)} 11. Bc2 b4 12. Ne4 Na5 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. e4 {This is the move which exploits the mistake ...dxc4. Black has abandoned the centre and White now completely controls it. In return Black has the upper hand on the queenside, but this even if this is not unimportant - has never - 'ceteris paribus' - been as important as the control of the centre. (Tarrasch)} b3 $6 15. Bb1 Bb4 16. Bg5 $1 Qg6 17. Bd2 $1 $18 Bxd2 18. Qxd2 Nc6 19. d5 Nd8 20. Ne5 Qh5 21. Nxc4 O-O 22. Nb6 Ra7 23. Ra3 f5 24. exf5 exd5 25. Rxb3 Qf7 26. Rd3 Bc6 27. Nxd5 Bxa4 28. Nc3 1-0


