1. d4 {1) Lasker:The international congress St.Petersburg 1909. Translation by R.Teichmann (2) Lasker: Der internationale Schachkongreß zu St.Petersburg. 1909. Berlin.1909. (Nachdruck Olms.1989.)} d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. dxc5 e6 4. e4 Bxc5 5. exd5 exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Ne2 {So far White has kept up the pressure on Black's d-pawn, but now he relaxes;} ({He might have gone on, for instance with} 10. Ba4 {a4-b3.}) 10... h6 11. Bh4 Be7 12. c3 Qb6 13. Qa4 Ne4 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Ned4 ({White does not play} 15. Bd3 {on account of} Qxb2 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Qxe4 Bd5 18. Qxe7 Rfe8 {with clear advantage for Black, since the c-pawn is difficult to defend.}) 15... Ng6 ({The reply to} 15... a6 {would be} 16. Qa3) 16. Qc2 Nf4 17. Rfe1 Rac8 18. Rad1 Bg4 19. Bf1 Qg6 {Overlooking the strength of White's next move.As it is, he accomplishes nothing more than a general exchange.} ({If he had played} 19... Rfe8 {first, he would have retained his advantage.}) 20. Ne5 Bxd1 21. Nxg6 Bxc2 22. Ne7+ Kh8 23. Nxc8 Bd3 24. Ne7 Bxf1 25. Rxf1 Re8 26. Nef5 Nd2 27. Rd1 Nc4 28. b3 Nb2 29. Rb1 Nbd3 30. Ne3 Rc8 31. g3 1/2-1/2


