1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bf4 dxc4 6. e3 Nb6 7. Bxc4 Nxc4 8. Qa4+ c6 9. Qxc4 Nd5 10. Be5 f6 11. Bg3 Qb6 12. Qe2 Bb4 ({For general reasons, I do not like} 12... Qa5 {The queen had just moved and the time was right for developing other pieces, too.} 13. O-O $1 {Entirely justified.} Nxc3 14. bxc3 Ba3 (14... Qxc3 15. e4 Ba3 16. Rab1 O-O 17. e5 $44) 15. Nd2 (15. Qc2 $142 $14) 15... O-O 16. Rab1 b6 17. Qc4 {L'Ami,E (2634)-Dvirnyy,D (2541)/Legnica POL 2013/CBM 155 (1-0, 68)} Re8 {...a6} 18. Qb3 Bf8 19. Nc4 Qh5 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 13. Rc1 (13. O-O Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxc3 15. Rab1 Qd8 16. Rfc1 Ba5 $13) 13... Nxc3 ({From the point of view of fighting for the light squares, I like} 13... Qb5 {more.} 14. Qxb5 (14. Qc2 O-O 15. Nd2 Qa6 16. Qb3 Bd7 17. e4 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Be7 19. c4 f5 $1 $132 20. f3 $140 c5 $132) 14... cxb5 15. Nd2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bd7 17. Ne4 Bc6 18. Nd6+ (18. c4 bxc4 19. Rxc4 Nb6 20. Nd6+ Ke7 21. Rc3 Rhd8 $17) 18... Ke7 19. c4 bxc4 20. Nxc4 Rac8) 14. bxc3 Ba3 15. Rd1 Qb5 16. c4 Qa5+ 17. Nd2 O-O 18. O-O b6 {But this looks entirely playable, too. Spielmann seemed to like playing in the spirit of the Grünfeld Defence, with piece pressure against a massive centre.} 19. f4 $6 (19. Nb1 Be7 20. Qc2 Ba6 (20... Re8) 21. Rc1 {[%cal Gc2e4]} Rfe8 22. Qe4 (22. Rfd1 Rad8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gc6c5]}) 22... Bf8 $11 23. Qxc6 $2 Rac8 $17) 19... Ba6 20. Be1 Qa4 21. Rf2 Rad8 $17 {Black has a harmonious position and is ready to fight over White's over-expanded centre.} 22. Rb1 c5 23. dxc5 Bxc5 24. Nb3 Ba3 25. Nd4 Bxc4 26. Qg4 f5 27. Qg3 Rf7 28. h3 Bc5 29. Rd2 Rc7 30. Kh2 Bxd4 31. exd4 Bd5 32. Qe3 Rdc8 33. Qe5 h6 34. Rbb2 Rc3 35. Qe2 Qa3 36. Rd1 Qxb2 37. Qxb2 Rc2 38. Rd2 Rxb2 39. Rxb2 Rc4 40. Bb4 a5 41. Bd6 Kf7 42. a3 Rc6 43. Bb8 Ke8 44. Ba7 Rc7 45. Bb8 Rc8 46. Be5 g6 47. g4 Rc3 48. gxf5 gxf5 49. Rxb6 Rxa3 50. Bd6 Rc3 51. Bc5 h5 52. h4 a4 53. Ra6 Rc2+ 54. Kg1 Rg2+ 55. Kf1 Rg4 56. Rxa4 Rxh4 57. Bd6 Rh1+ 58. Kf2 h4 59. Ra7 Rh2+ 60. Kf1 h3 61. Re7+ Kd8 62. Rh7 Ra2 0-1


