{Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'In this game, White has not one but two pawn breaks available to him. We could easily remodel Capablanca's words about the Alexander game to fit the new situation: -- 'From the look of the position it seems that White should prepare the pawn advance e3-e4. If Black is able to defeat this plan, or rather to prevent it, then once White has fixed the black pieces on the kingside he should quickly shift his attack to the queenside, and attack b5 with a2-a4.'' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): 'D38: Queen's Gambit Declined: Ragozin Defence (4 Nf3 Bb4) ''} 1. d4 d5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Opening = D38 - Damengambit-Ragosin Verteid /Queen's Gambit-Ragosin Defence'} 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nd7 4. Nc3 Ngf6 5. Bg5 Bb4 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qa4 $5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!?''} ({Capablanca played} 7. Qb3 {in the first turnus.}) (7. e3 c5 8. Bd3 $14) 7... Bxc3+ {?!} ({More fighting was} 7... c5 {. Spielmann is rather generous in giving up his dark-squared bishop without inflicting any real structural damage on White's queenside.} 8. dxc5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Qd4 (10. c6 {?!} Qc7 {!}) 10... Qa5 11. Qb4 $14 {!}) (7... Be7 {?} 8. Bxf6 {!} Bxf6 9. Nxd5) (7... Qe7 8. e3 (8. Bxf6 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxf6 10. e3 $14) 8... c6 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bh4 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Rfe1 Qf8 $14 {Alekhine}) 8. bxc3 O-O 9. e3 c5 $5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!?''} (9... Qe8 {%03'better is'} 10. Qc2 {!} (10. Bd3 {?} Ne5 {!}) 10... Ne4) 10. Bd3 c4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'N' 'N'} (10... Qe8 11. Qa3 Ne4 12. O-O b6 13. Bb5 Qe6 14. Bf4 Bb7 15. Rac1 Rfc8 16. c4 a6 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. cxd5 Qxd5 19. dxc5 Rxc5 20. Qb2 Ng5 21. Qe2 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Qxf3 23. gxf3 Bxf3 24. Rxc5 bxc5 25. Rb1 c4 26. Rb8+ Rxb8 27. Bxb8 c3 28. Be5 c2 29. Bb2 f6 30. Kf1 Kf7 31. Ke1 Ke6 32. Kd2 Bd1 33. e4 g5 34. Ke3 f5 35. exf5+ Kxf5 36. f3 h5 37. h3 Ke6 38. Bc1 Kd5 39. Kd3 Bxf3 40. Kxc2 g4 41. hxg4 hxg4 42. Bf4 Ke4 43. Bc7 Be2 44. a4 Kf3 45. a5 g3 46. Bxg3 Kxg3 47. Kb2 Kf4 48. Ka1 Ke3 49. Kb2 Kd4 50. Ka1 Kc3 51. Kb1 Kb3 52. Ka1 {½-½ Uhlmann,W-Palac,M/Werfen op 1991/TD 91\08}) 11. Bc2 {'with the idea' 0-0, Ne5, f4$36$16} Qe7 {?!} (11... Re8 {%03'better is'} 12. O-O Re6 {'with the idea' Ra6, Rb6 Alekhine} 13. Bf5 Ra6 14. Qc2 g6 15. Bh3 Nf8 16. Bxc8 Qxc8 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. e4 $14) 12. O-O {'with the idea' Rfe1, e4} a6 $6 {The advance of the a- and b-pawns provokes a minority attack. Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?!' JvR: 'The advance of the a- and b-pawns provokes a minority attack.' Neil McDonald: 'White has completed his development and needs to choose his plan. If he succeeded in advancing e3-e4, blasting open the e-file, he would gain a dangerous initiative, which could easily be converted into a direct assault on the black king: after all, White has a powerful pair of bishops as well as two rooks that could easily be brought into the attack. Alternatively, just dominating the e-file with the rooks after e3-e4 would give White excellent winning chances. --- In order to achieve his aim, White needs to play Rfe1 and Nd2, and then all is ready for e3-e4. The game continued:'' 'with the idea' b5} ({Correct is the immediate} 12... Qe6 $1 13. Nd2 Qg4 $1 14. Bf4 Nb6 15. Qa5 Bf5 $11) 13. Rfe1 {''} Qe6 (13... b5 {?!} 14. Qa5 Bb7 {?!} 15. Qc7 {! 'with the idea' 16.Qb7$18 'with the idea' 16.Bf6$18 Capablanca}) {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'The only way is by sticking his knight on e4, but unfortunately''} 14. Nd2 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'Spielmann, himself a master of attack, is aware that if he does nothing, 15 e4! will give the white pieces an irrepressible energy. Therefore he has to block the advance at all costs.'' ! 'with the idea' f3, e4$36$16} b5 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): 'last book move. Black threatens to win material: b5xa4''} (14... Ne4 {just loses a pawn to} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxc4 {. So first of all, he needs to defend the c4-pawn a second time.}) 15. Qa5 Ne4 $2 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?''} (15... Bb7 16. a4 (16. Qc7 {?!} Bc6 $14) (16. f3 {!? 'with the idea' a4$36$16 'with the idea' Bh4-f2, e4$36$16}) 16... Bc6) 16. Nxe4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'White terminates the opponent with strong threats'} dxe4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'Black has successfully accomplished his mission, as the e3-e4 advance is no more. However, in order to carry out his plan, he has been obliged to play 14...b5, which has exposed his queenside pawns to attack. Capablanca exploits this factor straightaway.''} 17. a4 $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'A classic example of the conversion of one advantage into another. A grandmaster class player like Spielmann would never have dreamt of playing 14...b5 if it hadn't been an essential component of the plan to stop e3-e4. --- Black now has severe difficulties in defending the b5-pawn, as he has no wish to be left with split pawns on a6 and c4 after 17...bxa4.''} Qd5 $2 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '?' Neil McDonald: 'Nonetheless, it looks as if Spielmann has found the saving move: the white bishop on g5 is attacked and when it retreats 18...Bb7, followed by 19...Bc6 if necessary, will hold together the queenside. But Capablanca has a little surprise in store...' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): '?''} (17... Rb8 18. Reb1 Rb6 (18... Qd5 19. Bf4 Rb6 20. axb5 Rxb5 21. Rxb5 axb5 22. Ba4 $18 {Alekhine} (22. Rb1 $18) 22... Ba6 {!!} 23. Qxa6 Ra8) 19. axb5 axb5 20. Qb4 Bb7 21. Ra5 Bc6 {offers more resistance.}) (17... Nb6 $142 $16) 18. axb5 $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'Here we see the conversion of the white bishop into three pawns - one of which will be an unstoppable passed pawn.' Komodo 9.02 64-bit (20s): '+-''} (18. Be7 {?!} Re8 19. axb5 Bb7 {!}) (18. Bf4 Bb7 19. Reb1 Bc6 $16) 18... Qxg5 (18... Bb7 19. bxa6 Qxa5 20. Rxa5 Rxa6 21. Rxa6 Bxa6 22. Bxe4 $18) 19. Bxe4 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'So White conquers the e4 point after all.''} Rb8 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): '+-' '+-'} (19... Ra7 20. b6 $1 {!} Qxa5 21. bxa7 $1 {(Alekhine). Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' JvR: '(Alekhine).''} Bb7 (21... Qxa1 22. Rxa1 Nb6 23. a8=Q (23. Rb1 $18 {!}) 23... Nxa8 24. Bxa8 $18 {Alekhine}) 22. Rxa5 Bxe4 $18 23. Rxa6 Ra8 24. Re2 Bb7 25. Ra5 Kf8 26. Rb2 Bc8 27. Rb4 Ke7 28. Rxc4 $18 {Capablanca}) 20. bxa6 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'The passed pawn on a6 quickly leads to threats' '+-' !} Rb5 ({Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'Neil McDonald: 'After''} 20... Qxa5 21. Rxa5 {and White wins the endgame. Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'and White wins the endgame. Neil McDonald: 'the passed pawn will cost Black a piece, leaving him two pawns down in the endgame.''} Rb3 22. Rc1 {!? 'with the idea' a7$18}) 21. Qc7 Nb6 (21... Qd8 22. Qxd8 Rxd8 23. a7 $18) 22. a7 Bh3 (22... Be6 23. f4 Qd8 24. Qxd8 Rxd8 25. Reb1 $18) (22... Bf5 23. Bc6 Rb2 $18) 23. Reb1 $1 {Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: '!' Neil McDonald: '!' Neil McDonald: 'White has no need to queen the pawn immediately, as if he is patient he can get more than a knight for it.''} (23. a8=Q $18 {!?}) (23. Qxb6 $18 {!?}) 23... Rxb1+ (23... Bd7 24. Rxb5 Qxb5 25. Rb1 $18) (23... g6 {does not help much} 24. Rxb5 Qxb5 25. gxh3 Qg5+ 26. Kf1 $18) (23... Rc8 24. Qxb6 Rxb6 25. Rxb6 g6 26. Rb8 $18) 24. Rxb1 f5 (24... Bxg2 25. Bxg2 Na8 26. Qd6 $18) (24... Nd7 {the last chance for counterplay} 25. Rb8 Nxb8 26. axb8=Q g6 $18) 25. Bf3 (25. Qxb6 $4 fxe4 26. Qe6+ Bxe6 $19) (25. Rxb6 fxe4 26. Qxc4+ Kh8 $18) (25. Qc5 h5 26. Rxb6 Rd8 27. Rb8 Kh7 28. a8=Q Rxb8 29. Qxb8 Qf6 30. Bd5 Bxg2 31. Qg8+ Kh6 32. Bf7 Kg5 33. Qc7 f4 34. Qxg7+ Kh4 35. Qg3+ fxg3 36. Qxg3#) 25... f4 (25... Bxg2 26. Bxg2 f4 27. exf4 Qg4 28. Qxb6 Qxf4 29. Qe6+ Kh8 $18) 26. exf4 {Capablanca got the first price for the best game. Fritz 5.00 (5s): 'JvR: 'Capablanca got the first price for the best game.' Neil McDonald: '. --- A splendid display that won the first brilliancy prize at the New York tournament. --- The moral is: if you believe you have made preparations for a pawn advance (or indeed any other plan) that suits the requirements of the position, and the opponent prevents it, look around to see what other opportunities have arisen for you.''} Qf5 (26... Qa5 27. Qxb6 Qxb6 28. Rxb6 Re8 29. Rb8 Bc8 30. g3 Re1+ 31. Kg2 Ra1 32. Rxc8+ Kf7 33. a8=Q Rxa8 34. Bd5+ Kf6 35. Rxa8 Ke7 36. Bxc4 g6 37. Ra7+ Kd6 38. Rxh7 Kc6 39. g4 Kb6 40. f5 gxf5 41. gxf5 Kc6 42. f6 Kd6 43. Kg3 Kc6 44. f7 Kd6 45. f8=Q+ Kc6 46. Qc5#) (26... Z0) (26... Rxf4 27. a8=Q+ {!} Nxa8 28. Rb8+ Rf8 29. Qxc4+ $18) 27. Rxb6 Bxg2 28. a8=Q Rxa8 29. Bxa8 $18 (29. Bxg2 $4 Ra1+ 30. Rb1 Qxb1+ 31. Bf1 Qxf1#) 1-0


