{Black to move. White's advantage in this position seems barely noticeable; his rook is more active and while both sides have three pawn-islands, Black's isolated e-pawn is slightly more significant than White's isolated a-pawn, but it hardly seems likely that this advantage will be sufficient to generate real winning chances.} 22... b5 $6 {It's hard to say that this move is a significant mistake, since the position remains clearly drawn, but it sows the seeds of Black's later difficulties. His idea is to play the rook to b6 and then a6 in order to attack White's weak a-pawn, but it soon becomes apparent that this plan is unrealistic and then Black suffers from the inflexibility of his queenside pawns.} ({I think playing ...b6 and ...c5 is a more straightforward way to draw, so as to open a file for counterplay with the rook. After, for example,} 22... b6 23. f4 Kd6 24. Ke3 c5 25. f5 (25. dxc5+ bxc5 26. Kd3 Rb8 27. Re2 Rb5 {is safe for Black}) 25... cxd4+ 26. cxd4 Re7 27. Kf4 b5 28. fxe6 Rxe6 29. Rxb5 Re2 {Black should have no difficulty reaching a draw.}) 23. Ke3 Rb8 24. h4 {[Diagram] Lasker realizes that Spielmann's intended plan is not dangerous and uses the tempo to gain space on the kingside.} Rb6 25. a4 $1 a5 {This is an other of those moves which, while not exactly wrong, limits Black's options and makes a slightly awkward position into one which requires accurate play. The problem is that pushing the pawn to a5 leaves Black's b5-pawn under constant attack and therefore his rook has to stay on the b-file to defend it.} ({Black's counterplay is brought to a grinding halt, since ...Ra6 is now impossible while} 25... bxa4 26. Ra5 a6 27. Rxa4 Kc7 28. Ra2 {leads to a position in which White has a very clear advantage as Black has several weak pawns. Note that although Black has an outside passed pawn, it is of no value since it cannot be advanced.}) ({It would have been better to play} 25... Kd6 26. g4 Rb7 27. Ke4 a6 28. h5 Rf7 {, which allows Black's rook to participate in the fight against White's kingside pawns. Although this is a rather passive plan, it's extremely hard for White to make progress, since after} 29. a5 Rf8 30. f4 Rf7 31. g5 Rf8 {there is no way for him to improve his position.}) 26. Kd3 Rb8 {[Diagram]} 27. Kc2 $1 {Moves such as this are the key to winning drawn positions. Although Black is somewhat tied up, it isn't easy to see a constructive plan for White, but Lasker finds a way to create play and force Black to defend carefully. The idea is to play c4, forcing Black to reply ...bxa4. White will continue Rxa5, and then his king will be positioned to prevent Black's rook from immediately penetrating along the b-file. 27...} Rb7 ({There is certainly an argument for playing 27...Kd6, since once the white rook reaches a5 there is the possibility of Ra7+ winning the g-pawn. Moving the king to d6 prevents this in advance, but one possible line indicates how accurately Black must now play in order to defend the position:} 27... Kd6 28. c4 bxa4 29. Rxa5 Rb4 30. Kd3 Rb3+ 31. Ke4 a3 32. Ra7 c5 33. Ra6+ Kc7 34. dxc5 Kb7 35. Ra5 Kc6 36. h5 Rb2 37. Rxa3 Rxg2 38. Ra6+ Kxc5 39. Rxe6 Rh2 40. Rg6 Rxh5 41. Rxg7 Kxc4 42. f4 Kc5 $1 {(the only drawing move)} 43. Rg6 Rh1 $1 44. f5 h5 45. Ke5 h4 46. Rh6 h3 {and Black saves the game by one tempo.}) 28. c4 {[Diagram] This is more troublesome than} (28. axb5 cxb5 29. c4 bxc4 30. Rxa5 Rb3 31. Ra7+ Kd6 32. Rxg7 Re3 {, since here Black's active rook insures him against defeat.}) 28... bxa4 29. Rxa5 Rb4 30. Kd3 Kc7 $1 {In this critical position, Spielmann finds the best defence, threatening to force a draw by ...Kb6 with a perpetual attack against White's rook since it dare not leave the a-file.} (30... Rb3+ $2 31. Ke4 a3 {is wrong here because} 32. Ra7+ Kc8 33. Ke5 {gives White's king too much activity}) (30... g6 $6 {is also doubtful due to} 31. Ra7+ Kc8 32. c5 Kb8 33. Ra5 Rb2 34. g4 Ra2 (34... Rb3+ 35. Ke4 a3 36. g5 hxg5 37. hxg5 {is also very unpleasant for Black}) 35. Ke4 g5 36. hxg5 hxg5 37. Ke5 Ra3 38. Kf6 Rxf3+ 39. Kxg5 {, when the passed g-pawn is very dangerous.}) 31. c5 {[Diagram]} Kb7 $2 {This passive move is too slow and gives White time to advance his king through the centre. Black could still have drawn, indeed he has a choice of methods, but it requires careful play:} (31... e5 $1 {(a surprising move, opening the fourth rank and so preventing the white king from advancing)} 32. dxe5 Kd7 33. h5 Ke6 34. Kc3 Rh4 35. Ra6 Kxe5 36. Rxc6 Kd5 37. Rc7 Rc4+ ({Black can also draw by} 37... a3 38. Rxg7 Ra4 39. Rd7+ Kxc5 40. Rd1 a2 41. Kb2 Rh4 42. Kxa2 Rxh5 43. Kb3 Rh2 44. Rd2 h5 {, when the advance of the h-pawn saves the game}) 38. Kb2 Rxc5 39. Rxg7 a3+ 40. Kxa3 Kd4 41. g4 Rc3+ 42. Kb4 Rxf3 43. Rg6 Rg3 {and White has no winning chances.}) (31... Rb3+ $1 {is an alternative drawing plan:} 32. Kc4 Ra3 33. Ra7+ Kb8 34. Rxg7 Rb3 {(now it's hard for the white rook to return to the a-file)} 35. Rg3 (35. Rg6 Rb1 36. Rxe6 a3 37. Re2 Rb2 38. Re1 a2 39. Ra1 Rxg2 {is also drawn}) 35... Kc7 36. h5 Rb2 37. f4 Kb7 {and White is in a curious zugzwang in which he must either surrender a pawn or allow the a-pawn to advance. Neither option gives him any winning chances.}) 32. Ke4 {Now White is free to advance his king to e5 either immediately or, better still, after the preparatory g4 and h5 32...} h5 {Black tries to prevent White from gaining further space on the kingside, but by now it makes no difference.} ({White also wins after} 32... g5 33. h5 Rb2 34. Ke5 Rxg2 35. Rxa4 g4 (35... Rh2 36. Kxe6 Rxh5 37. Kd7 {is also hopeless for Black}) 36. fxg4 Rxg4 37. Kd6 $1 e5 38. Rb4+ Kc8 39. Kxc6 Rf4 (39... Rxd4 40. Rb7 $1 Ra4 41. Rh7 Ra6+ 42. Kd5 e4 43. Kxe4 Kd8 44. Kd5 {is an easy win for White}) 40. Kd5 exd4 41. Rxd4 Rf5+ 42. Kc6 Rxh5 43. Rf4 {and Black is doomed because his rook is obstructed by his own pawn.}) 33. g4 hxg4 34. fxg4 g6 {[Diagram]} (34... Rb1 35. Rxa4 Rh1 36. h5 {offers Black no chances of saving the game.}) 35. Ke5 Rc4 36. h5 {This forcing continuation decides matters.} gxh5 37. gxh5 Rc1 38. Rxa4 Rh1 39. Kd6 $1 Rxh5 40. Rb4+ Kc8 41. Kxc6 Rd5 42. Ra4 Kb8 43. Kb6 {There is no defence to the advance of the c-pawn.} 1-0


