{And now let's see a game by two strong creative GMs from the past who, as you can guess ,invented more than one opening line...  But one of them is one of my favorites players of all time, the original but in the same time so logical... Ladies and gentlemen, be upstanding and greet with applause that great chess artist: Spielmann Rud-d-dolf! :-)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 d6 4. Nc3 Bf5 {And here we go with this Spielmann attack!  Even using it for the first time in this game, and maybe for the first time in history, I think you can guess why I didn't call it an anti-Gruenfeld... that could be quite confusing I guess, right?!:-))} 5. Nd2 ({Another interesting game of Spielmann went} 5. g3 h6 $5 (5... g6) (5... Qc8 $5) 6. Bg2 g5 7. h4 g4 8. Nd2 Nbd7 9. e4 Bg6 10. Nc4 Bg7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Qd2 Kh7 13. f3 b5 $1 $132 {Kmoch,H-Spielmann,R/Vienna 1922/HCL} (13... Bh5 $5 14. Qe2)) (5. Nh4 Bd7 ({In another interesting game Black got a nice position after} 5... Bg4 6. h3 Bd7 7. e4 e5 (7... b5 $5) 8. Nf3 (8. Nf5 Nxe4 9. Nxg7+ Bxg7 10. Nxe4 Qb6 $132) 8... b5 $1 9. Bg5 (9. Bxb5 Bxb5 10. Nxb5 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Nxe4) 9... b4 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nb1 f5 $1 $132 {0-1 Robveille,L-Dupre Guegan,M/Queven 1999/EXT 2002 (41)}) 6. e4 e6 (6... g6 {can't be bad, what is this  doing on h4??!}) (6... Qa5 7. Bd2 $1) (6... b5 $5 7. Bxb5 Bxb5 8. Nxb5 Nxe4 (8... Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nxe4) 9. O-O g6 $2 ({playable is} 9... a6 10. Na3 g6) 10. Re1 Nf6 11. Bf4 $16 {1-0 Kodinets,K-Gabrielian,A/chessassistantclub.com INT 2004/EXT 2006 (42)}) 7. Nf3 exd5 8. exd5 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. h3 Na6 11. a4 Nc7 (11... Nb4 $1 $36 {with f5 in the air seems very promising for Black.}) 12. O-O b6 13. Be3 Re8 14. Re1 Qc8 15. Ng5 Bf8 16. Bf3 Bf5 $13 17. g4 Bg6 18. h4 $6 h6 19. h5 Bxh5 $1 20. gxh5 hxg5 21. Bxg5 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Qf5 $17 {0-1 Majer,D-Maus,S/Germany 1993/EXT 1997 (35)}) 5... g5 $1 6. e4 Bg6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1 ({The famous Romanishin tried here} 9. a4 O-O ({Also not so clear is} 9... h6 10. f3 Ne5 11. g3 Qc7 12. f4 gxf4 13. gxf4 Ned7 14. f5 Bh7 15. Nc4 h5 $132) 10. Nc4 Nxe4 ({I would reccomened} 10... h6 $1 11. f3 Nh5 $132) 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxg5 $14 Ne5 (12... Nb6 13. Re1 $14 (13. Ne3 Bxb2)) 13. f3 Bf5 14. c3 a6 15. Qd2 Kh8 16. Ne3 Bd7 17. f4 Ng6 18. f5 $16 {1-0 Romanishin,O-Kayar,E/Istanbul 2003/CBM 096 (29)}) 9... O-O 10. Bf1 Ne5 (10... h6) ({Also interesting seems:} 10... Bh5 $5 11. f3 g4 12. f4 g3 13. Be2 gxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 h5 $1) 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 h6 {As I already mentioned before, exchanging pieces, especially a pair of 's making Black's life easier since he has less space, and now one piece less to take care of:-)} 13. Qd1 {Too passive.} ({More critical was something like} 13. h4 gxh4 (13... g4 14. Qg3 a6 15. a4 Qa5 $5 $132) 14. Qh3 h5 $5 (14... Qd7 15. Qxh4 Qg4) 15. Qxh4 Ng4 $1 $132) 13... Nd7 14. Be3 ({Again more cricital was} 14. h4 {but Black seems to do very well even after} Bf6 (14... f6 {is maybe OK but just looks too ugly}) 15. hxg5 hxg5 16. Re3 $1 Kg7 17. Rg3 Rh8 $1 {Again a gambit! Who cares about a little pawn here?!:-)} 18. Bxg5 Be5 19. Rh3 (19. f4 $4 Bd4+) 19... Rxh3 20. gxh3 Nf6 $44 {and even with a pawn down I would prefer Black, what about you guys?} (20... Qb6 $5 {is also good I guess})) 14... Ne5 15. f3 (15. h4 g4 {should keep the e5 for enough long time to get serious counterplay on the K side.}) 15... f5 $1 {This is in fact the position that I was dreaming to get when I found this f5+g5 line! Black breaks White's centre, gives life to his  on g6,  on f8 and even his queen and the other  can join the 'party' very soon! And yes, Black proudly but carefully can finally anounce a direct attack on the white monarch!} (15... a6 16. a4 Qa5 {will be another plan in another side of the board....but if we finally have our dream position, why not follow our dream?!:-)}) 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Bf2 Qe8 $1 {No need to explain this move, but just to mention that except bringing the  to attack, the small pawn on c2 is also a target! I always say that good plans are repaid with surprising bonuses!:-))} 18. Rc1 Qg6 19. Kh1 Rf7 $1 {Simple and good! The  coming to f8 is ready to 'smile' and help his friends as well!} 20. Qd2 Raf8 21. Be3 Qh5 $1 {improves the the  and prepares a g4-break; if that pawn is not taken it can get to g3 and make trouble...} 22. Bg1 Bc8 $1 {Even watching this great 'simple looking' game for at least 50 times, I still enjoy it so much, since it gives such a nice feeling of HARMONY!} (22... Bd7) 23. Be3 (23. Re4 {seems very solid, but Black still keeps making problems after:} g4 24. f4 g3 25. Be2 Ng4 26. h3 Qh4 $40) 23... g4 $1 24. f4 g3 $1 {This series of so many exclamation marks comes instead of a simple bravo announcement:-)} 25. h3 Ng6 {f4 is the new target now!} (25... Ng4 $1 {was more natural and probably stronger, but was easy to miss the next great combination that could happen after} 26. Be2 Rxf4 $3 27. Bxf4 Nf2+ 28. Kg1 Nxh3+ 29. gxh3 Bd4+ $1 (29... Qxh3 30. Bf1 Bd4+ 31. Re3 (31. Be3 Rxf1+ 32. Rxf1 Bxe3+ 33. Qxe3 Qh2#) 31... Qh4 $1 $19) 30. Qxd4 Qxh3 $1 $19) 26. Ne2 Qh4 27. c3 Bg4 $1 {The bishop is back in town again!} (27... Bf5 28. Bg1 Be4 (28... h5 {[%cal Gg7h6]}) 29. Nxg3 $1 {still keeps up the defence.}) 28. Qd3 (28. Qc2 Bf5 29. Qa4 Ne5 $1 (29... b5 30. Qxb5 Be4 31. Kg1) 30. Ng1 (30. fxe5 $4 Qxa4) 30... Ng4 $17) 28... Ne5 $1 {Start of a nice combination...} 29. fxe5 Bxh3 $4 {But oh, this move could destroy all this perfect game! Maybe it was a time trouble error or maybe not... After playing a great game, Spielmann suddenly misses a very important defence, that luckily his opponent also missed...} ({The winning move order was first} 29... Bf5 $1 {to kick the white  away from defence.} 30. Qb5 {and only now} (30. Bg5 hxg5 31. Qxg3 Bxe5 32. Qxh4 gxh4 $17 {This is positionaly lost for White, just look at the black pieces compared to White's!}) 30... Bxh3 $1 31. gxh3 Rxf1+ $1 32. Kg2 (32. Rxf1 Qxh3+ 33. Kg1 Qh2#) 32... Qe4+ $1 33. Kxg3 Qxe3+ 34. Kh2 (34. Kg4 Qg5#) 34... Qf2#) 30. Bg5 $4 {Returning the favour!} ({I guess that Gruenfeld was still shocked from the 'smooth looking' way he was outplayed with White; he could't believe that Spielmann would let him escape and he misses a golden chance!} 30. gxh3 $1 Rxf1+ {but is not forced to take it!} 31. Kg2 $1 $16 {I guess he just forgot about this move! Now I don't see any win for Black, something that is confirmed by the engine, but maybe one of you will come with new ideas to continue Black's attack?!} (31. Rxf1 $4 Qxh3+ 32. Kg1 Qh2#) 31... R1f2+ (31... R1f3 32. Rf1) (31... R1f3 32. Rf1) 32. Bxf2 Rxf2+ 33. Kg1 Qxh3 (33... Bxe5 34. Qg6+ Kh8 35. Rf1) 34. Qxg3 $1 $18 {is the problem, the white  doing the job of defence and after her last 'cleaning' job Black is suddenly lost...}) 30... Bxg2+ $1 {The next thing to come is mate on h2, so White resigned!  I hope you enjoyed this game, since I did enjoy watching it again!} 0-1


