1. d4 {1)Spielmann in WSZ 1934, S.45,73. 2)Gillam: Tournaments of 1934: Warsaw 1934 (22.-27. I).} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 {It is considered that this move gives Black equal play and that's why it is rarely played nowadays.} c5 5. dxc5 Nc6 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2 f5 ({The alternative is} 8... Bxc5 9. e3 O-O $11) 9. g3 (9. e3 $11) 9... Bxc5 10. Bg2 O-O ({Interesting is} 10... b6 $5 $11) 11. O-O b6 12. Qa4 (12. Rad1 $11) 12... Bb7 13. Nb3 Qe7 ({Black could have kept the bishop:} 13... Be7 $5 14. Nd4 $11) 14. Nxc5 ({White has nothing better. If he plays} 14. Rad1 {Black gets equal play after} Bb4 $11 (14... Rad8 {gives White a minimal advantage:} 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16. e3 $14)) 14... bxc5 15. e3 Rab8 $11 {Out of opening, the position is equal.} 16. f4 Nb4 ({Interesting is the possibility of} 16... g5 $5 $11) 17. Bxb7 Rxb7 18. Rad1 Nc6 ({Black should have looked for a counter-play on the kingside} 18... g5) 19. Qc2 g5 20. b3 Rf7 21. Qd2 gxf4 22. gxf4 Kh8 23. Kh1 Rb8 24. Rg1 $2 ({White does not make advantage of Black's inconclusive play. He could have got an advantage by playing} 24. Qd6 $16) 24... Rg8 25. Nb5 Rfg7 {Now Black has a good counter-play on the g-file} 26. Nd6 Nd4 $5 ({Simpler is} 26... Rxg1+ 27. Rxg1 Rxg1+ 28. Kxg1 Nd4 29. Nf7+ Qxf7 30. exd4 Qg7+ 31. Kf2 cxd4 32. Qa5 $11 {with equal ending.}) 27. Rxg7 Rxg7 28. Nc8 Qe8 29. exd4 Qxc8 30. d5 Qg8 ({Simple} 30... exd5 {led to a completely equal ending:} 31. Qxd5 Qe8 32. Qxf5 Qe3 $11) 31. Qc3 ({White should have tried} 31. Qe3 $14) 31... h6 (31... exd5 32. cxd5 Qe8 $11) 32. Rg1 Kh7 33. Rxg7+ Qxg7 34. Qd2 $11 {Completely equal queen ending.} Qf6 35. Kg2 Kg6 36. Kf3 e5 37. fxe5 Qxe5 38. Qe2 $4 ({If White wanted to play a pawn ending, much simpler was} 38. Qf4 $11 {After the game move, White is lost.}) 38... d6 $4 ({Black missed to enter a won pawn ending:} 38... Qxe2+ 39. Kxe2 Kf6 40. Ke3 Ke5 $19 {Three black pawns prevents White from creating a passed pawn which means that Black simply wins due to his passed f- pawn.}) 39. Qxe5 dxe5 40. h4 Kf6 41. a3 a5 42. Ke3 Ke7 1/2-1/2


