1. e4 {1)Capablanca Magazine 1912,p.26-27 2)Winter,E: Capablanca. p.52.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. a4 {What Lasker played in his match against Schlechter 1910 in four games.} (8. dxe5 $142) 8... Nxd4 {The right replay} 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Nc3 {It is known that Tarrasch is very studious and having been caught once in the trap by Maróczy it wasnot to be expected that he would allow himself to be caught ahagain without having something prepared. Spielmann lost this game more through lack of sense of reality tha anything else.} Nxc3 {Capablanca; This is the key to the entire variation.} (10... Nf6 11. Qxd4 c5 12. Qe5+ Be6 13. Bxd5 Nxd5 14. Rd1 Qd6 $11 {½-½ (47) Maroczy,G-Tarrasch,S San Sebastian 1911}) 11. bxc3 c5 {Discovered by Kostic.} 12. axb5 Be7 13. Qf3 {Capablanca: Incorrect, as b3 is paralyzed for the rest of the game.} (13. c4 $142 {Capablanca}) 13... Be6 14. Rxa6 O-O 15. cxd4 c4 {All this is Kostic's analysis.} 16. Ba2 (16. Ba4 Bd7 17. Qxd5 Rxa6 18. bxa6 Bxa4 19. Qxc4 Qa5 $17 {Capabalnca} (19... Qd7 $145 $19) 20. Bd2 Qxd2 21. Qxa4 g6 22. g3 Kg7 23. Qc4 $145 $11) 16... Rxa6 17. bxa6 Qa5 18. Bb1 c3 {Capabalnca; With this move the b1 is fastened in chains per secula seculorum.} 19. Qg3 Rc8 20. f4 $2 {Capabalnca: Bad, because it creates a hole at e4 for the enemy Bishop.} Bf5 21. Re1 Bf6 22. Kh1 h6 23. h3 Rb8 24. Be3 Qxa6 25. Rd1 Qa1 26. Qe1 Be4 27. Kh2 Be7 28. Qf1 f5 29. Re1 Bh4 30. g3 Be7 31. Bf2 Bd6 32. Rc1 Kh7 33. Re1 Rb6 34. Rc1 Ba3 35. Re1 Qb2 36. Qe2 Rb4 37. Rg1 Rb6 38. Re1 Qb5 39. Qh5 Qxb1 40. Rxb1 Rxb1 41. g4 Bc1 0-1


