1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Bf4 $6 Bf5 6. Nf3 e6 {Apparently this typical structure (here reversed whereas generally issued from 1.d4 d5 2. c4 e6 followed by White exchanging on d5) was scrutinized in the tournament to such an extent that it gave its name to it: The Karlsbad (or Carlsbad) structure!} 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nbd2 f6 $1 {Even here, with the London diagonal open, this idea poses White problems, for in return the opposing d5 pawn is protected against any further c3-c4 as in the previous game.} 9. Be2 (9. h4 Nh6 $1 10. Bxh6 (10. Be2 Ng4 11. Nf1 e5) 10... gxh6 11. Be2 O-O-O) (9. h3 g5 10. Bh2 h5 {Does not help White.}) 9... g5 (9... Nge7 10. O-O g5 11. Bg3 h5 12. h4 g4 13. Ne1 Bh6 14. Rd1 Bg6 15. Nd3 Bxd3 $1 16. Bxd3 f5 17. Be5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 O-O $2 (18... O-O-O 19. c4 Kb8 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Bc4 Nf4 $1 22. g3 Nh3+ 23. Kg2 Bxd2) 19. c4 d4 20. c5 Nd5 21. Nc4 $132 {Schmidt Schaeffer, S (2310)-Vonthron, H (2335) Germany 2004}) 10. Bg3 (10. Be3 Bd6) 10... h5 11. h3 Nge7 (11... Rc8 12. O-O Nge7 13. Qd1 Ng6 14. Ne1 h4 15. Bh2 Bd6 {Wohl, A (2388)-Laketic, G  (2446) Lido Estensi 2002 1/2(51)} 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Nxd3 $13) 12. O-O $2 {Castling 'coffin side'} (12. Nf1 Bg6 13. Ne3 Nf5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. a4 $13) 12... Bh6 13. Ne1 $2 (13. Qd1 $142 Ng6 (13... Bg6 14. Ne1 Nf5 $2 15. Bxh5) 14. Ne1 $140 g4 $1 15. hxg4 hxg4 16. Bxg4 e5 $44 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 18. Nc2 Nf4 $1 $40 19. Ne3 $2 Qh7) 13... g4 14. Qd1 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 gxh3 $17 {Black is a pawn up with an attack. No "overprotection" or "blockade", the most famous chess theoretician ever now finishes in style, somewhat helped, it has to be said, by the opponent's lack of defensive stubbornness.} 16. Nd3 b6 (16... h4 $1 17. Nc5 Qc8 18. Bd6 hxg2 19. Kxg2 b6 20. Ba6 Qd8 21. Nb7 Qd7 $19) 17. Rfe1 (17. Nf4 h4 $1 18. Bh5+ Kd8 (18... Rxh5 $4 19. Nxh5 {And f6 hangs.}) 19. Bxh4 hxg2 20. Rfe1 (20. Kxg2 e5) 20... Kc7 21. Bxf6 Rh7 $17) 17... h4 18. Bh2 Kf7 (18... hxg2 19. Nf4 h3 20. Bh5+ Kf8 21. Qe2 e5 $19) 19. g4 $6 (19. gxh3 $142 Bxh3 20. Kh1 $17) 19... hxg3 20. Bxg3 h2+ 21. Kg2 $2 (21. Kh1 Be4+ 22. f3 Rag8) 21... Be4+ (21... e5 22. dxe5 Be4+ 23. f3 Qh3+ 24. Kf2 (24. Kh1 Qxg3 25. fxe4 Rag8 26. exd5 Qg1+) 24... Rag8 25. Bf4 Qg2+ 26. Ke3 Nf5#) 22. Bf3 (22. f3 Bxd3 23. Bxd3 e5 24. Kh1 Qh3 25. Qf2 Rag8 26. Bxh2 exd4 $19 27. cxd4 $140 Nxd4 $1) 22... Nf5 23. Bxe4 $6 (23. Rxe4 dxe4 24. Bxe4 Rag8) 23... dxe4 24. Nf4 $2 {It seems that White systematically makes it as easy as possible for his attacking opponent in this game, but he might have simply overlooked, in his far ahead calculation, that he was just getting mated after} (24. Rxe4 Qd5 25. Qf4 Nxg3 26. fxg3 f5 27. Nf2 Kg6 (27... h1=Q+ 28. Rxh1 Rxh1 29. Kxh1 Kg6 30. c4 Qxc4 31. Re1) 28. c4 Qxc4 29. Re3 (29. Rf1 Qd5 30. Kh1 Raf8 31. Qf3 fxe4 32. Qg4+ Kh6 33. Qh3+ Qh5 34. Qxe6+ Kg7) 29... Nxd4 (29... Qd5+ 30. Qf3 Qxf3+ 31. Rxf3 Nxd4) 30. g4 Qd5+ 31. Kg3 Rac8 32. Re5 (32. gxf5+ Nxf5+) 32... Rc2 33. Rxd5 Ne2+ 34. Kf3 Nxf4 35. gxf5+ exf5 36. Rd4 Nh3) 24... e5 25. Ne2 Nh4+ $1 26. Bxh4 Qg4+ (26... Qg4+ 27. Ng3 Qf3+ 28. Kxh2 Rxh4+ 29. Kg1 Rah8) 0-1



